        'slug' => 'el-nido-honeymoon-quiet-side-five-day-couple-plan',
        'excerpt' => 'A calm five-day couple plan for El Nido that swaps the loud Tour A crowd for Nacpan dawns, a private island-hopping day, and Las Cabanas sunsets.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>El Nido is the postcard end of Palawan and the place most Filipino couples imagine when they say honeymoon. The standard Tour A boat day with 12 strangers, four loud GoPros, and a packed lunch on Big Lagoon is the version most people post about. This plan is the calmer one. Five days, two couple-only tours, two slow beach mornings, and one quiet inland day. Tara, here is the kwento by day.</p>
<h2>Before You Fly</h2>
<p>Fly Manila to Puerto Princesa, then a van transfer to El Nido town that takes around five hours along the north road. The faster option is flying directly to Lio Airport via AirSWIFT, which lands 10 minutes from town. The AirSWIFT route saves a full half-day each way and is the one most honeymooners take. Reserve the van or the flight one month out for the dry season window from November to May.</p>
<h2>Day 1: Arrive, Eat, Watch the Sunset</h2>
<p>Drop the bags by midday and skip any tour for the first afternoon. Walk the town beach for an hour, find a corner table at a beachfront kitchen for a calm lunch, then nap. Late afternoon, take a tricycle to Las Cabanas Beach, 15 minutes from town. Las Cabanas is the sunset spot of El Nido and the western horizon is wide and open. Order a couple of drinks at one of the open-air bars on the sand and let the first day end slow.</p>
<h2>Day 2: Private Island-Hopping (Tour A or Tour C)</h2>
<p>Book a private banca for two through your accommodation or a town agency. The shared tours are cheaper and the boats are full of barkadas with bluetooth speakers. The private option lets you pick the islands in any order, eat lunch on a quiet beach, and skip stops you do not want. For couples the cleanest itinerary is Big Lagoon at opening hour around 8 AM (the crowds arrive by 10), then Small Lagoon by kayak, then a beach lunch at Shimizu or Helicopter Island.</p>
<p>Bring a dry bag, a reef-safe sunscreen, and a hat. The boat day is six to seven hours under the sun and most couples underestimate the burn.</p>
<h2>Day 3: Nacpan Beach Day</h2>
<p>Nacpan is the long twin-beach 45 minutes north of El Nido town. The drive in is half the trip, on a road that cuts through the mountain interior and opens to a four-kilometer arc of sand and palm. Hire a tricycle for the day or rent a scooter if you ride confidently. Park at the southern end where the small beach shacks sell grilled seafood lunches.</p>
<p>Nacpan is shallow for the first 50 meters, which is good for swimming together, and the south side has a small viewpoint hill that takes 15 minutes to climb for the postcard photo. Stay until late afternoon, drive back to town for dinner. This is the day most couples remember.</p>
<h2>Day 4: Slow Morning, Inland Afternoon</h2>
<p>Sleep in. Breakfast on the room balcony if your accommodation has one. By late morning, head to the Nagkalit-kalit Falls or the Makinit Hot Springs, both inland from El Nido town and reachable by tricycle. The falls option is a 20-minute river walk to a small pool that is rarely full of people. The hot springs option is a 90-minute drive but the soak after a busy tour day is honest.</p>
<p>Back in town by late afternoon. Walk the back streets where the locals live. El Nido has a quieter side that the tour-day crowd never sees, and the alley karinderyas serve the better grilled fish dinners.</p>
<h2>Day 5: Sunrise, Pack, Fly Out</h2>
<p>Wake up at 5:30 AM for a sunrise walk on Caalan Beach, a 15-minute walk north of the town beach. Caalan is the quietest stretch within walking distance and the sunrise across Bacuit Bay is the cleanest morning of the trip. Coffee at one of the small cafes that open early on the main road, pack, and head to Lio Airport for the short flight back to Manila.</p>
<h2>Couple Notes</h2>
<p>Book a sea-view room. The difference between a garden room and a sea-view room in El Nido is the entire reason you came. Carry small bills for the tour operators and the tricycle drivers, since change is scarce. Bring one pair of reef shoes per person for the rocky lagoon entries. And do not pack a full dive trip into a honeymoon week. The quiet days are the ones that matter.</p>
<h2>Getting Around</h2>
<p>El Nido town itself is walkable. Tricycles handle the runs to Las Cabanas, Nacpan, and Caalan. For Nacpan and the inland falls, a scooter rental is the more flexible option if you ride. The town has no Grab. Cash is preferred almost everywhere; the ATMs on the main road occasionally run dry on weekends, so withdraw in Puerto Princesa if you transit through.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>December to early May is the dry window with the cleanest sea conditions for the boat day. The peak crowd weeks are Christmas, New Year, and Holy Week. The quietest months in the dry window are February and early March. June to October is the rainy side with stronger habagat winds; tours still run but the boat days get cancelled more often.</p>
