        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Boracay after the 2018 rehabilitation is a different island. The party strip on Station 2 still pulls a young crowd, but Station 1 has gone back to being the quiet end of the four-kilometer White Beach. This is the stretch where the sand is widest, the talong palms shade the loungers, and the sunset crowd thins out by 8 PM. For couples on a honeymoon week, Station 1 is the side that still earns the photo.</p>
<h2>Before You Fly</h2>
<p>Fly Manila to Caticlan or to Kalibo. Caticlan is the closer airport, around 15 minutes from the Cagban jetty port that connects to Boracay; Kalibo is one hour 30 minutes by van. Caticlan is the cleaner option but the smaller turboprops have weight limits and weather cancellations are more common during habagat. Most couples fly into Caticlan and out of Kalibo as a hedge.</p>
<p>The standard transfer chain is airport to jetty by van, jetty boat to Cagban port on the island, then tricycle or e-trike to the hotel. Allow 90 minutes from Caticlan airport to the room.</p>
<h2>Day 1: Arrive, Walk Station 1 to Station 3</h2>
<p>Drop the bags by midday and head straight to the beach. Station 1 has the wide white sand and the talong palms, and the walk south from Willy's Rock toward D'Mall takes around 25 minutes. This first walk is the orientation that every couple needs. You will know which kitchens look right for dinner and which beach loungers are within walking distance of the room. End at the D'Mall food strip for an early light dinner, then walk back north for the sunset.</p>
<h2>Day 2: Island-Hopping (Couple Banca)</h2>
<p>Book a private banca for the day through your accommodation. The shared tour boats stop at three islands with 30 to 40 strangers; the private option lets you pick the order and skip the busy snorkel stops. Standard couple route: Crystal Cove for the morning swim, Puka Beach for the long shell-sand walk and lunch, then back to White Beach by mid-afternoon. The puka shell stretch on the north end of Boracay is the postcard side most day-trippers miss.</p>
<p>Back to the room by 3 PM, nap, then walk the beach at sunset. Sunset on Boracay is the best two hours of the day and every couple should plan for it twice.</p>
<h2>Day 3: Slow Beach Morning, Helmet Diving or Parasailing</h2>
<p>Sleep in. Breakfast at one of the calmer beachfront kitchens on Station 1. Late morning, walk down to the watersports operators clustered around the Station 2 boundary. Helmet diving is the gentle option for couples who are not certified divers; parasailing is the bigger view option. Both are 30-minute activities and both run from 9 AM to 4 PM. Book on-site, not online. The cliff-jumping at Ariel's Point is a full-day boat trip out, worth it if you have an extra day.</p>
<p>Lunch on the beach, then afternoon reading on the loungers. This is a honeymoon day, not a checklist day.</p>
<h2>Day 4: Inland Boracay and Mount Luho</h2>
<p>Boracay has an inland side most visitors never see. Hire an e-trike for two hours and head to Mount Luho, the highest point on the island, for the 360-degree view of White Beach, Bulabog, and the smaller north coves. The viewpoint is a five-minute walk from the parking area and the late-afternoon light is the cleanest. Combine it with a stop at the Boracay West Cove or the Diniwid coves for the smaller-beach feel that White Beach no longer has.</p>
<p>Back to Station 1 for sunset and dinner.</p>
<h2>Day 5: Couples Massage, Slow Day</h2>
<p>Most accommodations on Station 1 offer in-room or beachfront couples massages. Book one for mid-morning and a second one for late afternoon if your honeymoon budget allows. In between, lunch on the beach and a swim. The middle day of a beach week is the one most couples overplan; resist the urge.</p>
<h2>Day 6: Sunrise, Bulabog Beach, Dinner</h2>
<p>The east coast of Boracay is Bulabog Beach, the kiteboarding side during the habagat months and the calmer family beach during the amihan months. Walk across the island (15 minutes on foot from Station 1) at sunrise; the sun rises on the Bulabog side and the photo is rarely taken. Coffee back on White Beach, slow day, sunset dinner on the sand.</p>
<h2>Day 7: Pack, Fly Out</h2>
<p>Sunrise walk on Station 1 if you have the early energy. Late checkout if your accommodation offers it. Tricycle to Cagban port, boat to Caticlan jetty, van to the airport. Allow three hours from the room to the boarding gate.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>November to May is the dry amihan season with calm sea conditions on the White Beach side. The peak crowd weeks are Christmas, New Year, and Holy Week. The quietest months in the dry window are September, October, and February. Habagat months from June to October bring rain and the swimming side shifts to Bulabog.</p>
