        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Panglao is the small island off the southwestern tip of Bohol, connected by two short bridges, and it is the beach base most couples use when they say a Bohol honeymoon. The island has three coasts: the busy Alona side, the calmer Dumaluan side, and the quietest Doljo side. A three-day honeymoon hits all three without ever feeling rushed.</p>
<h2>Before You Fly</h2>
<p>Fly Manila to Bohol Panglao International Airport, a one-hour 20-minute flight, with Cebu Pacific, Philippine Airlines, or AirAsia. The airport is on Panglao itself, around 20 minutes by tricycle or van to the Alona Beach area and around 25 minutes to Doljo or Dumaluan. Most accommodations include the airport transfer for honeymoon bookings.</p>
<h2>Day 1: Arrive, Doljo Sunset</h2>
<p>Drop the bags by midday and skip Alona for the first afternoon. Take a tricycle to Doljo Beach on the western tip of Panglao, around 10 minutes from the main road. Doljo is the quietest of the three coasts: long arc of white sand, almost no resorts on the beach itself, and a public stretch that fills with local families on weekends and is empty mid-week.</p>
<p>Walk the beach until late afternoon. Doljo faces west and the sunset over the Bohol Sea is open and unobstructed. Dinner back at the room or at one of the small kitchens along the Doljo road.</p>
<h2>Day 2: Pamilacan Dolphin Watching, Alona Dinner</h2>
<p>Pamilacan is the small island 40 minutes by banca off the southern Bohol coast, and the dawn dolphin-watching run is the honest ethical version of the more-marketed Balicasag dolphin tour. Wake up at 5 AM, banca out from Baclayon by 6 AM, and the spinner dolphins surface in pods of 50 to 100 around the deep channel between Pamilacan and the mainland. The boat keeps a distance and the dolphins decide whether to swim alongside.</p>
<p>Continue to Pamilacan island itself for a late breakfast and a snorkel along the protected reef. Back to Panglao by early afternoon, nap, then walk the Alona Beach strip for dinner. Alona has the busiest food scene on Panglao and a honeymoon dinner along the beach with a calm wine is a clean evening.</p>
<h2>Day 3: Bohol Countryside Tour, Fly Out</h2>
<p>The Bohol countryside tour is the standard inland day that pairs the Chocolate Hills, the Loboc River lunch cruise, the tarsier sanctuary at Corella, and the Loay viewpoint into a single hired-car day. Book the car for an 8 AM pickup, return to Panglao by 4 PM. The Chocolate Hills are the postcard but the tarsiers and the Loboc River cruise are the parts couples actually remember.</p>
<p>If your flight is the next morning, fly out from Panglao Airport with a slow last morning at the beach. If your flight is same-day, return the car by 3 PM and head to the airport.</p>
<h2>Where to Stay</h2>
<p>Alona is the busy strip with the food and the activity centers. Dumaluan is the quieter middle stretch with the wider sand and the family resort row. Doljo is the quietest western tip with the fewest resorts. For a honeymoon, Dumaluan is the best base: close enough to Alona for dinner, far enough to sleep in calm.</p>
<h2>Getting Around</h2>
<p>Tricycles are the standard transport on Panglao. Scooters are available for rent in the Alona area. Grab does not operate on the island. The main road that loops Panglao is around 25 kilometers and a slow scooter loop in late afternoon is one of the better couple activities. Bring cash; the smaller kitchens do not take cards.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>March to June is the calmest sea window with the best snorkel visibility. The peak crowd weeks are Holy Week and Christmas. July to October is the habagat side with stronger winds; boat days get cancelled more often. November to February is the cool dry window with the cleanest evenings.</p>
<h2>Couple Notes</h2>
<p>Order the kinilaw at any Panglao kitchen; the southern Visayan version with coconut milk and calamansi is the lighter take on the dish. Pack reef shoes for the Pamilacan run and a light rain jacket for the boat day. The honeymoon week is the one to splurge on a beachfront room; for Panglao that means a Dumaluan or Doljo room, not Alona.</p>
