        'excerpt' => 'A scooter-loop honeymoon week on Siquijor that pairs Salagdoong cliff dives with Cambugahay tarzan swings, slow Paliton sunsets, and quiet San Juan dinners.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Siquijor is the small island province south of Cebu and Dumaguete, ringed by a single 75-kilometer coastal road that you can loop in one easy scooter day. Most travelers visit Siquijor as a two-day weekend off Dumaguete. For honeymooners, the case for staying a full week is the slowness. The roads are empty, the coves are mostly public, and the evenings are the cleanest you will find in the Visayas.</p>
<h2>Before You Fly</h2>
<p>Fly Manila to Dumaguete in one hour 20 minutes, then take the fast ferry from Dumaguete port to Siquijor port in 45 minutes. The ferry is operated by Ocean Jet and Aleson with departures roughly every two hours during daylight. Tricycle or rented scooter from Siquijor port to the San Juan coast in around 30 minutes.</p>
<h2>Day 1: Arrive, San Juan Sunset</h2>
<p>San Juan is the main couple base on Siquijor: long stretch of white sand, the sunset coast, the quiet food scene. Drop the bags, walk the Paliton Beach side at late afternoon (10 minutes north of San Juan town), and watch the first sunset of the trip. Paliton is the most-photographed beach on the island and faces west; the small forest behind the sand is the backdrop most travelers know from the postcard.</p>
<h2>Day 2: Cambugahay Falls and Lazi Side</h2>
<p>Cambugahay Falls is a three-tier waterfall and pool on the southern side of the island, around 30 minutes by scooter from San Juan. The locals run a tarzan-swing rope at the second pool and the swim is the calmest of any falls in the Visayas. Go before 9 AM to skip the day-tripper crowd from Dumaguete; the pool fills up by mid-morning.</p>
<p>Continue south to Lazi for the old century-old church and convent, two of the better-preserved Spanish-era buildings outside Manila. Lazi convent has a small heritage museum and the wood-and-coral construction is unusual. Lunch at Lazi, then loop back to San Juan via the southern coast.</p>
<h2>Day 3: Salagdoong and the East Coast</h2>
<p>Salagdoong Beach is the cliff-dive cove on the eastern side of Siquijor, around an hour scooter ride from San Juan through a forest road that the locals call the haunted road. The drive is the highlight; the canopy closes overhead for most of the ride. Salagdoong itself has a 10-meter and a 15-meter cliff dive platform built into the rocks. The cove is small, the sand is white, and the water is clear enough to see the bottom from the platform.</p>
<p>Couples who do not dive can swim the cove and watch the divers; the cove is shallow on the western edge and easy for non-swimmers too. Lunch at the small beach kitchen, then loop back to San Juan via the northern coast for a long scooter sunset run.</p>
<h2>Day 4: Slow Day, Massage, Old-Enchanted Balete Tree</h2>
<p>Sleep in. Late breakfast on the beach. Mid-morning, scooter to the old-enchanted balete tree at Campalanas in Lazi, the 400-year-old centuries-old balete that has been a Siquijor heritage stop for decades. The small pool at the base has fish-spa fish that nibble feet; couples either love it or hate it. The drive there and back is 90 minutes total.</p>
<p>Afternoon couples massage at one of the beachfront spa kitchens in San Juan, then sunset on Paliton again.</p>
<h2>Day 5: Capilay Spring and Maria Inland</h2>
<p>Capilay Spring is a freshwater public pool in San Juan town proper, a few minutes from the coast. The locals use it daily and the cold spring water is a clean alternative to the sea swim. Spend the morning there, then scooter to the Maria municipality on the southeastern side for the Kagusuan Beach side, one of the quieter coves that takes a 10-minute walk down from the road. Most travelers skip Kagusuan; for couples, that is the point.</p>
<h2>Day 6: Folk Healing Tour or Snorkel</h2>
<p>Siquijor is known for its folk-healing tradition and the San Antonio area has practitioners who still hold the traditional bolo-bolo and tawas ceremonies for visitors. The visit is more cultural than spiritual and the elders explain the rituals in calm detail. Alternatively, a half-day snorkel off Tubod or Tongo coves is the gentle water alternative. Pick one.</p>
<h2>Day 7: Slow Morning, Ferry Out</h2>
<p>Sunrise walk on the San Juan beach. Late breakfast. Ferry back to Dumaguete by mid-afternoon, then fly home from Dumaguete airport the next morning. Most couples build one night in Dumaguete city on the return for the Rizal Boulevard dinner and the morning tempura row.</p>
<h2>Getting Around</h2>
<p>Scooters are the standard couple transport. Rental shops cluster around San Juan town and Siquijor port. Helmets are required and the police checkpoints near Larena and Siquijor port do enforce. Cash works everywhere; the few ATMs are in Siquijor town proper and run dry on weekends.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>March to June is the calmest sea window. November to February is the cool dry window with the cleanest evenings. July to October is the habagat side with stronger winds; ferries still run but sea crossings get rougher.</p>
