    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    // 6. DUMAGUETE HONEYMOON: THREE-DAY DAUIN APO SIDE
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://taraletsanywhere.com/dumaguete-honeymoon-dauin-apo/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Tara Lets Anywhere',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Dumaguete Honeymoon: A Three-Day Dauin and Apo Island Side',
        'slug' => 'dumaguete-honeymoon-three-day-dauin-apo-side',
        'excerpt' => 'A three-day Dumaguete honeymoon for couples who want a Rizal Boulevard evening, an Apo Island turtle swim, and a Dauin black-sand morning.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Dumaguete is the small university city on the southeastern tip of Negros Oriental, and the southern coast just outside the city (Dauin, Zamboanguita, and Apo Island) has some of the cleanest reef diving in the Visayas. For couples who want a calmer city base for the evenings and a quiet sea morning for the days, the Dumaguete and Dauin pair works as a three-day honeymoon.</p>
<h2>Before You Fly</h2>
<p>Fly Manila to Dumaguete in one hour 20 minutes, with Cebu Pacific or Philippine Airlines. The airport is in the city itself, 10 minutes by tricycle to the Rizal Boulevard area. Most accommodations either in Dumaguete city or in Dauin (45 minutes south) will arrange the airport pickup.</p>
<h2>Day 1: Arrive, Rizal Boulevard Evening</h2>
<p>Drop the bags by mid-afternoon. Walk the Rizal Boulevard from the port to the Silliman gates at late afternoon; the boulevard is a one-kilometer seafront promenade that opens to the Cebu Strait, and the late-afternoon light makes the walk easy. The tempura row at the southern end of the boulevard is the local snack stop. Order the squid balls, the kikiam, and a buko juice; eat at the seawall.</p>
<p>Dinner at one of the kitchens along Hibbard Avenue or the boulevard itself. Sans Rival for the silvanas as the dessert stop on the way back is the standard couple finish.</p>
<h2>Day 2: Apo Island Day Trip</h2>
<p>Apo Island is the small marine sanctuary 45 minutes by banca from the Malatapay port in Zamboanguita, around an hour south of Dumaguete by van. The island is famous for the turtle population that grazes the seagrass in the shallow eastern bay. Most snorkel days see five to fifteen turtles, sometimes more. The reef wall on the western side has the bigger coral gardens and the deeper water.</p>
<p>The day starts at 7 AM with the van pickup, banca out by 9 AM, lunch on Apo or back at Malatapay, return to Dumaguete by mid-afternoon. Reef shoes are not required (the boat lands on a sandy beach) but a long-sleeve rashguard is the better sun cover than reapplying sunscreen. Pack a dry bag for the camera and the wallet.</p>
<p>Back to the room by late afternoon, nap, then a slow dinner. Apo days are tiring and the second-day energy drops by 7 PM.</p>
<h2>Day 3: Dauin Black-Sand Morning, Fly Out</h2>
<p>Dauin is the coastal town 30 minutes south of Dumaguete and the black-sand coast is the macro-diving capital of the Philippines. For non-divers, the morning walk on the Dauin beach is the calm version: black volcanic sand, clear shallow water, and the Apo Island silhouette on the horizon.</p>
<p>Most Dauin resorts offer a half-day snorkel that hits the house reef and the close-in marine sanctuary; the visibility is not as crystal as Apo but the night-octopus and the seahorse population at the shallow muck sites is what Dauin is known for. Couples who dive should consider a third day to do a proper Dauin macro morning; couples who do not dive can skip and head back to Dumaguete after lunch.</p>
<p>Fly out from Dumaguete airport in the late afternoon. Cebu Pacific has a 4 PM Manila flight that fits a same-day return.</p>
<h2>Where to Stay</h2>
<p>For couples, the choice is between a Rizal Boulevard or Hibbard Avenue room in Dumaguete city, or a Dauin beachfront resort closer to the diving. The city option has the food scene and the night walks; the Dauin option has the sea and the dawn calm. Most honeymoon weeks split: two nights in the city, one or two in Dauin.</p>
<h2>Getting Around</h2>
<p>Tricycles inside Dumaguete are cheap and easy. The Dauin and Zamboanguita coast needs a van rental or a habal-habal for the day. Grab works inside the city. Cash is preferred for most kitchens and tricycle drivers.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>March to June is the calmest sea window with the best Apo Island visibility. November to February is the cool dry window with the cleanest evenings. July to October is the habagat side with stronger winds; Apo trips get cancelled more often during these months.</p>
<h2>Couple Notes</h2>
<p>The Dumaguete food scene is the underrated draw for couples. The tempura row is the famous one but the small Hibbard kitchens for sisig, pochero, and budbud kabog are the actual local plates. Order one budbud kabog (a millet sticky-rice cake) with sikwate (Visayan chocolate) for breakfast at the small Si-Ana spot near Silliman; it is the calmer way to start a Dauin morning.</p>
HTML,
        'meta_title' => 'Dumaguete Honeymoon: Three-Day Dauin and Apo Island Side | Resort Guru PH',
        'meta_description' => 'A three-day Dumaguete honeymoon: Rizal Boulevard, Apo Island turtles, Dauin black-sand morning, and Silliman-side dinners. Calm couple plan, Negros Oriental.',
        'tags' => 'Dumaguete, Honeymoon, Dauin, Apo Island, Negros Oriental',
