    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.alittlewanderlust.com/samal-honeymoon-davao/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'A Little Wanderlust PH',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Samal Honeymoon: A Davao Side Three-Day Quiet Plan',
        'slug' => 'samal-honeymoon-davao-side-three-day-quiet',
        'excerpt' => 'A three-day Samal honeymoon for couples flying into Davao: a Pearl Farm afternoon, Hagimit Falls morning, and a Talicud island day off the quieter side.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Samal is the large island that sits across the Davao Gulf from Davao City, connected by a 10-minute barge from Sasa wharf. For a honeymoon, Samal is the rare Philippine resort island that is still mostly off the international weekend track, which means the resorts are quieter and the small kitchens on the back roads are still the local versions. Three days is enough to taste the island without rushing.</p>
<h2>Before You Fly</h2>
<p>Fly Manila to Davao in one hour 50 minutes, with Cebu Pacific, Philippine Airlines, or AirAsia. From Davao airport, the standard transfer is a 30-minute drive to Sasa wharf, then a 10-minute barge to Samal, then a 20-minute drive to the resort. Most accommodations on Samal arrange the full chain as a single transfer.</p>
<h2>Day 1: Arrive, Resort Side, Sunset</h2>
<p>Drop the bags by mid-afternoon. Most Samal resorts have a private beach side with calm shallow water that is good for swimming. Walk the beach, swim, nap. Late afternoon, ask the resort about a sunset banca or a short paddle in front of the property. Samal faces west across the gulf to the Davao City skyline and the sunset has the city lights coming on across the water as backdrop.</p>
<p>Dinner at the resort or at a small kitchen along the Penaplata road (the main road on Samal). The Samal seafood is the cleaner version because the gulf is calmer and the fish reaches the kitchen faster.</p>
<h2>Day 2: Hagimit Falls Morning, Talicud Afternoon</h2>
<p>Hagimit Falls is a small forest-shaded pool 20 minutes from the Penaplata side of Samal, a quiet alternative to the bigger waterfalls in Davao region. The pool is shallow and the surrounding trees keep the area cool even at midday. Visit before 10 AM to skip the day-tripper crowd. The road in is paved most of the way; a tricycle handles it.</p>
<p>Afternoon banca to Talicud island, the smaller island 30 minutes off Samal's western coast. Talicud is the quieter sibling of Samal: cleaner sand, fewer resorts, and several public coves like Isla Reta and Babu Santa that are open for day swims. Pick one cove, bring lunch from a Samal kitchen, swim for two hours, banca back by 4 PM.</p>
<h2>Day 3: Pearl Farm Day Tour, Fly Out</h2>
<p>Pearl Farm is the historic pearl-cultivation resort on the southwestern Samal coast, and the day tour with lunch is the way to see the property without staying overnight. The boat leaves from the Davao City pickup point or from a Samal pickup; check the day-tour schedule the week before. The included swim at Malipano cove is the cleanest snorkel water on the Samal side.</p>
<p>Back to the resort by 4 PM. Pack, take the early evening barge back to Sasa, fly out from Davao airport. The 8 PM Manila flight fits a same-day return.</p>
<h2>Where to Stay</h2>
<p>The eastern Samal coast (facing the Davao Gulf interior) has the bigger resorts and the calmer water. The western Samal coast (facing Talicud) has the quieter properties and the better sunset. For a honeymoon, the eastern side has the cleaner snorkel water but the western side has the better evenings.</p>
<h2>Getting Around</h2>
<p>Tricycles handle the short hops on Samal. Most resorts have shuttle vans for the longer runs to Hagimit, Penaplata, and the Talicud port. Scooter rentals are available but the Samal roads can be rough on the back side; bring closed shoes.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>March to October is the drier window with the calmest gulf conditions; the Davao region does not follow the standard Luzon seasons because it sits south of the typhoon belt. November to February is also fine. The wettest months are December and January with afternoon rain.</p>
<h2>Couple Notes</h2>
<p>Order the kinilaw at any Samal kitchen; the Davao version uses tabon-tabon and mango that gives the dish a different finish than the Visayan version. The Davao durian is in season from August to October; even non-durian eaters should try a small portion of the local Davao durian on a Samal weekend, since the variety here is the cleaner one. Bring a long-sleeve rashguard for the Talicud day; the sun on the gulf is stronger than it looks.</p>
