    // 9. TAGAYTAY BABYMOON: PREGNANCY-FRIENDLY WEEKEND
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://taraletsanywhere.com/tagaytay-babymoon/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Tara Lets Anywhere',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Tagaytay Babymoon: A Pregnancy-Friendly Weekend from Manila',
        'slug' => 'tagaytay-babymoon-pregnancy-friendly-weekend',
        'excerpt' => 'A Tagaytay babymoon weekend for second-trimester moms: cool air, short walks, calm bulalo lunches, and no zip lines or long drives.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Tagaytay is the easiest babymoon destination from Manila. The drive is short, the air is cooler, the elevation is low enough to be safe (around 600 meters), and most of the activity can be done from the car or a short walk. For couples expecting in the second trimester, this is the weekend that does not require a flight, a long sea crossing, or a four-hour van ride.</p>
<h2>Before You Drive</h2>
<p>Most OB-GYNs clear second-trimester travel between 14 and 28 weeks for short trips that stay below 2,000 meters elevation. Tagaytay sits at 600 meters, well within the safe range. Carry a copy of the maternity record, the OB-GYN clearance note, and the prenatal medication. Leave Manila by 6 AM Friday to avoid the worst of the long-weekend traffic; the drive is 90 minutes off-peak.</p>
<h2>Friday Afternoon: Arrive, Slow Ridge Walk</h2>
<p>Drop the bags at the hotel by mid-afternoon. Skip any active plan for the first day. Walk the hotel garden or the ridge promenade in front of the property for 20 to 30 minutes; the cool air and the Taal view are the point. Most ridge hotels have a balcony or a garden chair that faces the volcano; spend the late afternoon there with a calm drink.</p>
<p>Dinner at the hotel or at a quiet ridge restaurant within five minutes by car. The bulalo and tawilis options are the local orders. Avoid the loud strip kitchens; the babymoon side of Tagaytay is the slow side.</p>
<h2>Saturday: Caleruega Visit, Mahogany Bulalo, Slow Afternoon</h2>
<p>Late breakfast. By mid-morning, drive to Caleruega in Nasugbu (40 minutes from the ridge). Caleruega is a Dominican retreat house with a small chapel, a garden, and short flat walkways that are easy for a pregnant mom to walk. The site has shaded benches throughout, restroom facilities, and the kind of slow garden pace that the trip is for. Free entry on most days.</p>
<p>Lunch back in Tagaytay at the Mahogany Market bulalo strip. The bulalo here is the local version, the kitchens are open-air, and the seating is calm by mid-day. Order a small bowl to share if appetite is light. The marrow and the slow-cooked beef are the protein hit that most pregnant moms appreciate after the long morning.</p>
<p>Afternoon back at the hotel. Most ridge hotels have pools and spa services with maternity-safe options. Book a side-lying prenatal massage if the spa offers one; most Tagaytay spas have a trained therapist who handles pregnancy massages.</p>
<h2>Sunday: Taal Viewpoint, Slow Drive Out</h2>
<p>Wake up at the room's pace, not a tour pace. Late breakfast on the balcony if the room has one. Mid-morning, a short drive to the Taal viewpoint at People's Park or one of the cafes that face the volcano. The viewpoints have paved walking paths and short distances; the People's Park summit is a five-minute gentle climb that most second-trimester moms can do without strain.</p>
<p>Lunch at the hotel before checkout. Drive out by 1 PM to beat the Sunday return traffic; the return drive should be 90 minutes if you leave on time. Take a break at the SLEX rest stop midway; pregnant moms should not sit for the full 90 minutes without a stretch.</p>
<h2>What to Pack</h2>
<p>The pregnancy-friendly Tagaytay packing list is short. Light layers because the ridge can drop to 18 to 20 degrees on evenings; a comfortable walking pair of shoes for the Caleruega and viewpoint walks; the prenatal record and medication; a refillable water bottle; and snacks for the drive. Most ridge hotels have humidifiers if you ask; the cool dry air can be a little harsh on the throat overnight.</p>
<h2>What to Avoid</h2>
<p>Skip the zip lines, the Sky Ranch rides (the Ferris wheel is fine; the swing rides are not), the long Caleruega hikes (the chapel and garden are fine; the longer trail down to the cliffside is not), and the late-night dinners that push back the sleep schedule. The babymoon week is about cool air and rest, not a checklist.</p>
<h2>Getting Around</h2>
<p>A private car is the only sensible option for a pregnancy weekend. The ridge stretches 10 kilometers and tricycle rides are bumpy on the Tagaytay road. Bring a comfortable pillow for the back support during the longer drives within the area.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>December to February is the cool dry window with the cleanest evenings and the lowest temperatures on the ridge. March to May is hotter but still cooler than Manila. Avoid the rainy June to October if possible; the ridge gets fog and the Taal view often disappears, plus the slippery walkways at Caleruega are a hazard for pregnant moms.</p>
HTML,
        'meta_title' => 'Tagaytay Babymoon: Pregnancy-Friendly Weekend | Resort Guru PH',
        'meta_description' => 'A second-trimester babymoon weekend in Tagaytay: cool air, short walks at Caleruega, Mahogany bulalo, and a slow Taal viewpoint morning. Calm pregnancy plan.',
