    // 10. PANGLAO BABYMOON: CALM THREE-DAY PACE
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.wanderingfeetofmine.com/panglao-babymoon/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Wandering Feet of Mine',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Panglao Babymoon: A Calm Three-Day Pace',
        'slug' => 'panglao-babymoon-calm-three-day-pace',
        'excerpt' => 'A second-trimester babymoon plan on Panglao: Doljo Beach mornings, a slow Loboc River afternoon, prenatal spa, and no boat tours.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Panglao works as a babymoon destination because the flight is short, the airport is on the island itself, and the calm Dumaluan and Doljo coasts have the kind of shallow swim water that does not require a boat to reach. For second-trimester moms looking for a sea trip that does not involve a five-hour banca day, Panglao is the safer pick over El Nido or Coron.</p>
<h2>Before You Fly</h2>
<p>Most airlines allow pregnancy travel up to 32 weeks without a medical certificate and up to 36 weeks with one. The Manila to Bohol-Panglao route is one hour 20 minutes, a comfortable single flight. Carry the maternity record and the OB-GYN clearance note in the carry-on. Pre-book the airport transfer with the resort to skip the haggling on arrival.</p>
<h2>Day 1: Arrive, Slow Beach Walk, Early Dinner</h2>
<p>Drop the bags by mid-afternoon and skip any active plan. Walk the resort beach for 20 to 30 minutes; the Dumaluan and Doljo coasts have the wide flat sand that is easy for a pregnant mom to walk on. Swim the shallow lagoon if the tide is in; the water is warm and supportive, which is what most second-trimester moms find relieves the lower back pressure.</p>
<p>Early dinner at the resort or at a nearby kitchen. Order a calm Visayan fish dish, the kinilaw if the OB-GYN cleared raw fish, otherwise the steamed or grilled version. Skip the spicy kitchens; the Bohol food scene has plenty of mild options.</p>
<h2>Day 2: Loboc River Lunch Cruise, Tarsier Sanctuary</h2>
<p>The Loboc River lunch cruise is the babymoon-friendly version of the Bohol countryside tour. The floating restaurant is a flat barge that drifts slowly upriver to a small waterfall; the trip is 90 minutes total with a buffet lunch on board. No bumpy roads, no climbing, no boats with rough seas. The river is calm year-round.</p>
<p>Pair the cruise with a stop at the Corella tarsier sanctuary (45 minutes from Loboc), the ethical version of the tarsier experience. The walkways are short, flat, and shaded. The tarsiers sleep through most of the day so the visit is quiet by design.</p>
<p>Skip the Chocolate Hills viewpoint climb on a babymoon. The 214-step climb at the Carmen viewpoint is the standard tourist climb and the local advice is that it is not babymoon-friendly. The view from the parking lot is the alternative.</p>
<p>Back to Panglao by mid-afternoon. Slow swim, early dinner.</p>
<h2>Day 3: Prenatal Spa, Slow Beach Morning, Fly Out</h2>
<p>Slow morning at the resort. Most Panglao spas offer a prenatal massage with a side-lying setup; book one for late morning. The hour-long session combined with the slow swim and the cool morning sea breeze is the calm-day that most babymoons are built around.</p>
<p>Lunch at the resort, then a slow walk on the beach before the airport transfer. Fly out by mid-afternoon from Panglao airport.</p>
<h2>What to Pack</h2>
<p>The Panglao babymoon list includes the maternity record, the prenatal medication, a wide-brim hat for the sea sun, a long-sleeve rash guard for the swim, a reef-safe sunscreen with a high SPF, mosquito repellent for the inland Loboc afternoon, and a comfortable beach cover-up. Most resorts have humidifiers and prenatal pillows if you ask in advance; mention the pregnancy when booking.</p>
<h2>What to Avoid</h2>
<p>Skip the Pamilacan dolphin-watching dawn (the 5 AM start, the rough banca crossing, and the unstable boat platform are not babymoon-friendly), the Hinagdanan Cave climb (slippery stone steps), the ATV ride through the Chocolate Hills area, and any island-hopping day. The babymoon week is about beach and river, not banca.</p>
<h2>Getting Around</h2>
<p>Pre-arranged van transfers through the resort are the cleanest option. Tricycles are fine for short hops in the Dumaluan and Doljo areas but the unpaved back roads can be bumpy. The Loboc cruise pickup typically includes the transfer.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>March to June is the calmest sea window with the warmest swim water. November to February is the cool dry window. Avoid June to October if possible; the habagat winds make the sea choppier and the rainy afternoons disrupt the slow river-cruise plan.</p>
