        'excerpt' => 'A second-trimester El Nido babymoon that swaps the long banca days for short-tour picks, slow beach mornings, and a Nacpan land day.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>El Nido looks like a difficult babymoon destination because most of the famous activity is on a six-hour boat day. The standard Tour A and Tour C runs are not babymoon-friendly: long sun exposure, choppy crossings, and rocky lagoon entries. But El Nido has a calmer side that pregnancy travelers can still enjoy. The trick is to pick the shorter half-day tours, the land-side activities, and a resort room with shade and a balcony.</p>
<h2>Before You Fly</h2>
<p>Most airlines allow pregnancy travel up to 32 weeks without a medical certificate and up to 36 weeks with one. Fly Manila to Lio Airport via AirSWIFT, which lands 10 minutes from El Nido town. The longer Puerto Princesa to El Nido van transfer is five hours and not recommended for second-trimester moms; the AirSWIFT route is the babymoon pick.</p>
<h2>Day 1: Arrive, Caalan Beach Sunset</h2>
<p>Drop the bags by mid-afternoon at a resort with a balcony and shaded outdoor area. Walk the Caalan Beach side, a 15-minute easy walk north of El Nido town. Caalan is the quietest beach within walking distance, with a long flat stretch of sand and almost no boat traffic. Sit on a beach lounger, watch the late-afternoon sun, and enjoy the slow start.</p>
<p>Early dinner at a calm town kitchen. Order the grilled lapu-lapu or the fresh kinilaw if the OB-GYN cleared raw fish; the Palawan version with calamansi is the lighter take.</p>
<h2>Day 2: Half-Day Tour D or Snorkel-Light</h2>
<p>The pregnancy-friendly El Nido tour is Tour D, the half-day boat that hits Cadlao Lagoon and Pasandigan Cove with a beach lunch. The crossing is shorter (45 minutes one way), the lagoon entry is gentle, and the lunch is on a flat sand beach. Book a private banca rather than the shared tour; a private boat gives you control over the pace and lets you skip stops if the seas pick up.</p>
<p>Alternative for moms who do not want a boat day: a Nacpan Beach drive (45 minutes by tricycle or van from town), a long beach lunch, and a calm afternoon under the palm trees. Nacpan has a four-kilometer arc of sand and shallow swim water; no boat required.</p>
<p>Back to the resort by mid-afternoon. Slow swim, early dinner.</p>
<h2>Day 3: Prenatal Massage, Las Cabanas Sunset</h2>
<p>Slow morning. Late breakfast on the balcony if the room has one. Most El Nido resorts offer a prenatal massage with a side-lying setup; book one for late morning. The town-center spas also have prenatal options at lower rates.</p>
<p>Afternoon at Las Cabanas Beach (15 minutes by tricycle from town). Las Cabanas is the sunset beach of El Nido and the western horizon is wide and open. Sit on a beachfront chair, watch the sun set behind the Bacuit islands, and let the second-trimester slow time take over. Dinner at one of the Las Cabanas kitchens or back in town.</p>
<h2>Day 4: Slow Morning, Fly Out</h2>
<p>Sunrise walk on Caalan if the morning energy is there. Late breakfast. Pack, head to Lio Airport for the short flight back to Manila.</p>
<h2>What to Pack</h2>
<p>The El Nido babymoon list includes the maternity record, the prenatal medication, a wide-brim hat, a long-sleeve UPF rash guard, a reef-safe sunscreen, mosquito repellent for the evenings, and a refillable water bottle. Bring sturdy walking sandals for the rocky beach edges and reef shoes if you plan to enter the Cadlao Lagoon water.</p>
<h2>What to Avoid</h2>
<p>Skip the full-day Tour A and Tour C runs (Big Lagoon and Hidden Beach involve climbing over rocks), the kayak rentals (paddling for pregnant moms with belly-up positions is not recommended), the inland Makinit hot springs (the heat and the long bumpy road are both risks), and any scooter rentals (the El Nido roads have potholes that are dangerous for pregnancy).</p>
<h2>Getting Around</h2>
<p>Tricycles handle El Nido town and the runs to Las Cabanas and Caalan. For Nacpan, hire a van for the day; the road is rough in patches. Most resorts include the Lio Airport transfer in the babymoon booking. Cash is preferred almost everywhere; the ATMs run dry on weekends so withdraw on arrival.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>December to early May is the dry window with the cleanest sea conditions and the smallest crossings. The quietest months in the dry window are February and early March. Avoid June to October; the habagat winds make even the half-day tours rougher.</p>
HTML,
        'meta_title' => 'El Nido Babymoon: Pregnancy-Friendly Tour Picks | Resort Guru PH',
        'meta_description' => 'A second-trimester El Nido babymoon: half-day Tour D, Nacpan land day, Caalan sunset walks, and prenatal spa. Calm, couple-paced, AirSWIFT to Lio.',
        'tags' => 'El Nido, Babymoon, Pregnancy Travel, Palawan, Couple Plan',
