    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    // 12. LA UNION BABYMOON: SLOW COAST WEEKEND
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://taraletsanywhere.com/la-union-babymoon-slow-coast/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Tara Lets Anywhere',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'La Union Babymoon: A Slow Coast Weekend',
        'slug' => 'la-union-babymoon-slow-coast-weekend',
        'excerpt' => 'A second-trimester babymoon weekend on the Bauang side of La Union: calm beach walks, slow Ilocano lunches, and no surf school for this trip.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>La Union is most famous for surfing, which is not the right activity for a pregnant mom. But the province has a calmer southern coast at Bauang and Aringay where the sand is darker, the waves are smaller, and the resort row has the swimming pools that work better for a babymoon weekend than the San Juan surf strip. For couples expecting in the second trimester who can drive (not fly), this is the slower option from Manila.</p>
<h2>Before You Drive</h2>
<p>From Manila, take NLEX to SCTEX to TPLEX, exit at Rosario, then drive up the Manila North Road to Bauang. Total drive is five hours off-peak. Leave Manila by 6 AM Friday and break the trip with a long stop at the Subic or Tarlac rest stops. Pregnant moms should not sit for more than two hours without a stretch break. Carry the OB-GYN clearance, maternity record, and prenatal medication.</p>
<h2>Friday Afternoon: Arrive, Slow Bauang Beach Walk</h2>
<p>Drop the bags by late afternoon. Walk the Bauang beach for 20 to 30 minutes; the Paringao stretch is the resort row and the sand is darker but the swim entry is gentle and the water is calm. Skip swimming on the first afternoon; let the body adjust. Sit on the resort beach chair, watch the sunset over the West Philippine Sea, and let the long drive rest off.</p>
<p>Early dinner at the resort or at a small Ilocano kitchen along the highway. Order the pinakbet (Ilocos version with bagoong isda), the bagnet if the OB-GYN cleared the fatty pork, and the grilled tilapia. The Ilocano kitchens skew salty so ask for less bagoong if the cravings are mild.</p>
<h2>Saturday: Ma-Cho Temple, Halo-Halo de Iloko, Slow Pool Afternoon</h2>
<p>Late breakfast. Mid-morning drive to Ma-Cho Temple in San Fernando (20 minutes north). The temple is on a hill with a short climb up the stairs from the parking area; take it slow with frequent rests. The dragon-tiled courtyards and the bay-view balcony are the calm photo spots. Free entry.</p>
<p>Walk down to the San Fernando city center for lunch at Halo-Halo de Iloko. Order the regular Ilocos halo-halo with pinipig and corn (skip the longganisa ice cream version for a babymoon; the savory experiment can upset a sensitive stomach). Ilocos longganisa for the breakfast the next day as pasalubong.</p>
<p>Afternoon back at the resort. Most Bauang resorts have proper swimming pools, which are safer for pregnancy than the sea swim. A slow pool soak is the best babymoon afternoon. Side-lying prenatal massage at the resort spa if available.</p>
<h2>Sunday: Slow Morning, Drive Out</h2>
<p>Wake up at the room's pace. Late breakfast on the resort beach with the morning view. Walk the beach for 15 minutes before checkout. Skip the surf strip; the urbiztondo crowd is loud and crowded and not the babymoon vibe.</p>
<p>Drive out via the same TPLEX route. Build in a long lunch stop at Tarlac or Pampanga rest stops; the five-hour drive needs the break. Back in Manila by mid-evening.</p>
<h2>What to Pack</h2>
<p>The La Union babymoon list includes the maternity record, prenatal medication, a wide-brim hat, a long-sleeve cover-up for the beach, a comfortable swimsuit for the pool, a refillable water bottle, snacks for the drive, and a pillow for back support during the longer car drive. Most resorts have spa pillows and prenatal-massage therapists; mention the pregnancy when booking.</p>
<h2>What to Avoid</h2>
<p>Skip the surf lessons, the Tangadan Falls trek (the 20-minute river-crossing walk has slippery rocks), and the long inland drives to San Gabriel and Naguilian. The babymoon weekend should stay close to the Bauang coast.</p>
<h2>Getting Around</h2>
<p>The private car you drove from Manila is the cleanest transport. Tricycles handle short hops within Bauang but the bumpy roads are not ideal for pregnancy. The Ma-Cho Temple and the San Fernando lunch stops are easy from the resort by car.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>October to March is the cool dry season with the cleanest beach days. April to September is the warmer wet side. Avoid Holy Week and Christmas long weekends because the TPLEX traffic is heavy and the long drive becomes a pregnancy risk.</p>
