    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    // 16. SENIOR-FRIENDLY VIGAN: HERITAGE PACE TWO-DAY
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.wanderingfeetofmine.com/senior-friendly-vigan/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Wandering Feet of Mine',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Senior-Friendly Vigan: A Heritage-Pace Two-Day Plan',
        'slug' => 'senior-friendly-vigan-heritage-pace-two-day',
        'excerpt' => 'A two-day Vigan plan for senior travelers: calesa tours over walking, ground-floor heritage stops, and slow Ilocano lunches.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Vigan is one of the friendlier heritage destinations for senior travelers because the Calle Crisologo cobblestone street is short (around 500 meters) and the calesa horse-drawn carriages handle the longer connections between sites. The trick for a senior weekend is to skip the walk-everywhere approach and book the half-day calesa tour that hits the standard six stops with a driver who manages the pace.</p>
<h2>Before You Fly</h2>
<p>Fly Manila to Laoag in one hour 15 minutes with Cebu Pacific or Philippine Airlines. From Laoag, hire a private van for the 80-kilometer drive south to Vigan, around 90 minutes. Skip the long overnight bus from Cubao; the 10 to 12 hour ride is hard on seniors. The flight option is the senior-friendly pick.</p>
<p>Carry the maintenance medication, the senior PWD card, and the maternity or medical contact card if applicable. Most Vigan heritage hotels have ground-floor or elevator-accessible rooms; request one when booking.</p>
<h2>Day 1: Arrive, Calesa Half-Day, Plaza Burgos Dinner</h2>
<p>Drop the bags by midday at a heritage hotel on or near Calle Crisologo. Lunch at the hotel or at a small Ilocano kitchen on the heritage street. Order pinakbet Ilocos-style with bagoong isda, the Vigan longganisa, the bagnet if the senior can handle the fatty pork, and the dinengdeng vegetable soup.</p>
<p>Afternoon calesa tour. The Vigan calesa drivers run a standard six-stop loop: Plaza Salcedo (the dancing fountain), the Vigan Cathedral, Plaza Burgos, the Bantay Bell Tower (drive past the climb; the view from the road is fine for seniors), the Crisologo Museum (ground floor only), and the Hidden Garden (lunch optional, otherwise just a walk through). The driver manages the pace and the carriage has padded seats with rest pillows.</p>
<p>Dinner at the Plaza Burgos food stalls for the empanada and okoy. The plaza has flat paved seating and the empanada is the Vigan signature; order one Vigan empanada per senior and share. Late evening dancing-fountain show at Plaza Salcedo runs at 7:30 PM and 8:30 PM. Free, family-friendly, easy to watch from a paved bench.</p>
<h2>Day 2: Slow Crisologo Morning, Pottery Stop, Fly Out</h2>
<p>Late breakfast at the heritage hotel. Mid-morning walk on Calle Crisologo. The street is closed to vehicles in the morning hours; the cobblestones are uneven so seniors should walk slowly with a cane or a family member's arm. Stop at the heritage shops for souvenirs: Ilocos longganisa, sukang Iloko vinegar, tupig (sticky rice grilled in banana leaves), abel Iloko handwoven blankets.</p>
<p>Optional stop at the Pagburnayan pottery workshop, the centuries-old jar-making site on the outskirts of Vigan. The workshop is a single ground-floor area; seniors can sit on a bench and watch the potter shape the burnay jar in 10 minutes. Free entry, small donation for the photo.</p>
<p>Lunch at a Vigan heritage restaurant. Cafe Leona on Calle Crisologo has a heritage setting and the menu covers Ilocano standards. Drive back to Laoag for the late afternoon flight to Manila.</p>
<h2>What to Pack</h2>
<p>The senior Vigan list includes the maintenance medication, the senior PWD card, comfortable walking shoes with rubber soles for the cobblestones (no leather soles; they slip), a cane if used at home, light layers for the cool dry evenings (Vigan drops to 22 to 24 degrees on November nights), a wide-brim hat for the midday heat, and a refillable water bottle.</p>
<h2>What to Avoid</h2>
<p>Skip the Bantay Bell Tower climb (90 steps up a narrow wooden staircase), the Crisologo Museum upper floors (steep wooden stairs, no elevator), and the long La Paz Sand Dunes 4x4 ride near Laoag (the bumpy ride is hard on senior backs). The senior Vigan trip is about the calesa and the slow lunches.</p>
<h2>Senior Discounts</h2>
<p>The Philippine senior citizen card gives a 20 percent discount at most Vigan restaurants, hotels, and the calesa rides. Bring the original card; photocopies are sometimes refused. The discount applies even to foreign senior cards if the senior is over 60.</p>
<h2>Getting Around</h2>
<p>Inside Vigan, the calesa is the senior-friendly transport. Tricycles handle short hops outside the heritage zone but the suspension is rough. For the drive between Laoag and Vigan, a private van with a driver is the cleanest option for seniors.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>October to March is the cool dry season with the cleanest weather for the calesa rides. The Vigan evenings drop to 22 to 24 degrees on November nights, which makes the Plaza Burgos dinner pleasant. April to September is hotter; the cobblestones radiate heat and the calesa rides become uncomfortable.</p>
