    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    // 17. PWD-ACCESSIBLE BORACAY: WHEELCHAIR ROUTES
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.alittlewanderlust.com/pwd-accessible-boracay/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'A Little Wanderlust PH',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'PWD-Accessible Boracay: Wheelchair-Doable Routes on White Beach',
        'slug' => 'pwd-accessible-boracay-wheelchair-routes',
        'excerpt' => 'A wheelchair-doable Boracay plan covering Station 1 beachfront resorts with ramps, e-trike transport, and the easier sand stretches.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Boracay is more PWD-friendly than most Philippine beach destinations because the new D'Mall promenade has paved walkways, the Station 1 sand is wide and flat, and the e-trike fleet that replaced the older tricycles is easier to board with mobility aids. Wheelchair travelers can still enjoy the White Beach experience if they pick the right resort, the right transfer chain, and the right times of day.</p>
<h2>Before You Fly</h2>
<p>Fly Manila to Caticlan for the closer airport transfer. The Caticlan jetty to Cagban port boat ride is short (15 minutes) and the boat staff will help board a wheelchair manually; pre-call the resort to coordinate. From Cagban port, an accessible e-trike or van takes you to the resort. Most Station 1 resorts can arrange the full transfer chain for PWD guests; mention the wheelchair when booking.</p>
<p>The Philippine PWD card gives a 20 percent discount on resort rates, restaurant bills, and most island activities. Bring the original card; foreign PWD documentation is honored on a goodwill basis. The senior PWD card (60+) also applies to seniors with mobility constraints.</p>
<h2>Day 1: Arrive, Resort Beach Lounger, Sunset</h2>
<p>Drop the bags at a Station 1 resort with documented PWD-accessible rooms. Several Station 1 properties have roll-in showers, grab bars, and ramp access from the beach to the room. Settle in, and head to the beachfront. The Station 1 sand is the widest stretch on Boracay; the talong palms shade the beach loungers and the sand near the water is firm enough to roll a beach wheelchair on if your resort has one.</p>
<p>Sunset on Station 1 is the easiest PWD activity on Boracay. The beach is flat, the loungers are on the firm sand at the high-tide line, and the sunset crowd is calm by 6 PM. Order a calm drink from the beachfront kitchen, watch the sun set behind Diniwid.</p>
<h2>Day 2: Beach Wheelchair Morning, D'Mall Afternoon</h2>
<p>Several Station 1 resorts and watersports operators have beach wheelchairs (the wide-balloon-tire kind) that roll on soft sand. Book one for a morning beach walk; the rate is modest and the staff push the chair for guests who cannot self-propel on sand. The wide-tire wheelchair lets you reach the actual waterline, which a standard chair cannot do.</p>
<p>Afternoon at D'Mall. The new D'Mall promenade has paved walkways throughout, accessible restrooms, and ramps at every corner. The food strip has step-free entry to most kitchens; the shops are mostly accessible. A 90-minute slow loop through D'Mall is the standard afternoon for PWD travelers; the shaded paths make it easier than the sand walk in midday heat.</p>
<h2>Day 3: Optional Helmet Diving, Slow Beach Day</h2>
<p>Helmet diving is one of the few PWD-doable Boracay watersports. The setup involves sitting on a metal stool underwater with a clear glass helmet over the head; the helmet provides air and the experience is at chest depth in calm sea. The operators assist with the transfer from the boat to the underwater stool. This is one of the more accessible Philippine watersports for travelers with lower-body mobility constraints.</p>
<p>Skip the parasailing, the jet ski, and the cliff-jumping at Ariel's Point; these require full mobility and are not safe for wheelchair travelers.</p>
<p>Slow afternoon on the beach lounger. Sunset, dinner, and a calm last evening.</p>
<h2>Day 4: Pack, Fly Out</h2>
<p>Slow morning at the resort beach. Late checkout if the resort offers it. The transfer chain back to Caticlan airport takes around 90 minutes. Allow three hours from the room to the boarding gate.</p>
<h2>Where to Stay</h2>
<p>Several Station 1 resorts on the beachfront have documented PWD-accessible rooms with roll-in showers and grab bars. Look for properties that confirm in writing the room features; some resorts list accessibility but the actual room layout has steps that the listing did not mention. Pre-book through email and confirm by phone the week before arrival.</p>
<h2>Getting Around</h2>
<p>E-trikes are the standard Boracay transport and they are easier to board with a wheelchair than the older tricycles. For longer transfers, pre-book a van with a driver. Grab does not operate on Boracay. The walk along D'Mall is fully paved; the walk along the beach itself requires either a beach wheelchair or firm-sand timing.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>November to May is the dry amihan season with calm sea conditions on the White Beach side. The Station 1 sand is firmest during low-tide hours; check the local tide chart for the day's window. Avoid the habagat months from June to October; the rain and the wind make the beach less PWD-friendly.</p>
HTML,
        'meta_title' => 'PWD-Accessible Boracay: Wheelchair Routes on White Beach | Resort Guru PH',
        'meta_description' => 'A wheelchair-doable Boracay plan: Station 1 resort picks, beach wheelchair morning, D Mall afternoon, helmet diving option, and accessible transfer chain.',
        'tags' => 'Boracay, PWD Travel, Wheelchair Accessible, Station 1, Accessibility',
        'cover_destination_key' => 'boracay',
    ],

    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    // 18. KID-FRIENDLY SUBIC: THREE-DAY TESTED PLAN
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://taraletsanywhere.com/kid-friendly-subic/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Tara Lets Anywhere',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Kid-Friendly Subic: A Three-Day Tested Plan',
        'slug' => 'kid-friendly-subic-three-day-tested-plan',
        'excerpt' => 'A three-day Subic family plan that actually works with kids: Zoobic morning, Ocean Adventure afternoon, JEST animal walk, and a beach day at Camayan.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Subic is the family weekend that most Manila parents reach for first because the drive is reasonable, the activity menu is built for kids, and the SBMA road network is easy to drive with a family in tow. The three-day plan below is tested with kids aged five to ten, the age range that most enjoys the Subic theme parks. Older teens enjoy the place too but the program shifts toward Ocean Adventure shows and the beach.</p>
<h2>Before You Drive</h2>
<p>From Manila, take NLEX to SCTEX, then exit at Subic Bay Freeport. Drive is around two hours 30 minutes off-peak. Leave Manila by 5 AM Friday to skip the worst of the morning traffic. Pre-book hotel rooms two weeks out for the long weekends; Subic fills up.</p>
<p>Pre-book the Zoobic, Ocean Adventure, and JEST tickets online to skip the gate lines. Most parks have a kids-under-three free policy; bring birth certificates if your kid looks older.</p>
<h2>Day 1: Arrive, Zoobic Park, Slow Evening</h2>
<p>Drop the bags by midday at a Subic hotel. The SBMA properties cluster around the boardwalk area and have pool access; pick one with a pool because the kids will demand a swim after the long drive.</p>
<p>Lunch at the hotel or a Subic kitchen. The boardwalk area has the family-friendly Filipino-American chains plus a few local kitchens.</p>
<p>Afternoon at Zoobic Park. Zoobic is the safari-style park where you board a converted jeep with cage screens and drive through a real tiger enclosure. The kids will remember the tiger jeep for years. The rest of the park has the croc walk, the savannah area, and the small petting zoo. Allow three to four hours. Wear closed shoes; the park is uneven in parts.</p>
<p>Back to the hotel by 5 PM for the pool, the dinner, and a quiet evening. Subic evenings are darker than Manila so the kids sleep earlier.</p>
<h2>Day 2: Ocean Adventure Day</h2>
<p>Full day at Ocean Adventure, the marine park on Camayan Point. The day has scheduled shows: the dolphin show in the morning, the sea lion show late morning, the bird show after lunch. Each show is around 25 minutes; the kids love them all. Between shows, walk the open-air tanks: the dolphin viewing tank, the shark tank, the freshwater habitat.</p>
<p>Lunch at the in-park restaurant or pack a meal. The park has shaded picnic areas for families with packed food. Pack water bottles, sunscreen, hats, and a change of clothes for the kids; the wet-area zones will splash.</p>
<p>Optional add-on: the dolphin encounter or the sea lion encounter, which lets the kids stand in shallow water with a trainer and a marine mammal for 20 minutes. Booked separately at the park gate or online; the slots fill up so book early.</p>
<p>Back to the hotel by 5 PM. Pool, dinner, sleep.</p>
<h2>Day 3: JEST Animal Walk, Drive Out</h2>
<p>Late breakfast. Mid-morning at JEST Camp, the jungle survival training camp that opens to families for a short animal-walk and Aeta-village experience. The walk includes a parrot stop where the kids can hold a colorful parrot on the shoulder, an iguana stop, and a python stop for the brave ones. The Aeta-village section has a short cultural presentation. Allow two to three hours.</p>
<p>Lunch at JEST or back at the hotel. Pack and check out by 2 PM. Drive out via SCTEX, back in Manila by 5 PM if you leave by 2.</p>
<h2>Where to Stay</h2>
<p>Subic hotels cluster in the boardwalk area near the bay or in the harbor point area. For families, pick a hotel with a pool and kid-friendly food options; the standalone hotels without pools become long evenings with restless kids. Camayan Beach Resort near Ocean Adventure is the closer option if you plan to spend most of the trip at Ocean Adventure.</p>
<h2>What to Pack</h2>
<p>The Subic kid list: sunscreen, hats, swim clothes, change of clothes for the wet-area splashes, closed shoes for Zoobic, sandals for the pool, mosquito repellent for JEST, water bottles, snacks for the car. Bring kid medications including a basic fever and tummy kit.</p>
<h2>Kid Notes</h2>
<p>Most Subic parks have stroller rentals at the gate. Bring your own if your kid is between four and six; the gate strollers are limited in number and run out by midday. Diaper-changing stations are available at the main parks. The toilet facilities are clean and the staff are family-friendly.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>November to May is the cool dry season with the cleanest weather for the outdoor parks. December and January are crowded with holiday families; book early. June to October is the rainy side; the parks still operate but the outdoor shows get cancelled on heavy rain days.</p>
HTML,
        'meta_title' => 'Kid-Friendly Subic: Three-Day Tested Plan | Resort Guru PH',
        'meta_description' => 'A three-day Subic family plan tested with kids 5-10: Zoobic tiger jeep, Ocean Adventure shows, JEST animal walk, and slow pool evenings.',
        'tags' => 'Subic, Family Travel, Kid-Friendly, Zoobic, Ocean Adventure',
        'cover_destination_key' => 'subic',
    ],

    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    // 19. KID-FRIENDLY TAGAYTAY: WEEKEND WITH KIDS
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.wanderingfeetofmine.com/kid-friendly-tagaytay/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Wandering Feet of Mine',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Kid-Friendly Tagaytay: A Weekend Actually With Kids',
        'slug' => 'kid-friendly-tagaytay-weekend-actually-with-kids',
        'excerpt' => 'A two-day Tagaytay weekend that works with kids: Sky Ranch, Puzzle Mansion, Yoki House, ridge picnics, and cool evenings.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Tagaytay marketed as a kid-friendly destination often means Sky Ranch and nothing else. This plan covers the actual two-day weekend that a family with kids aged four to twelve can do without burning out. The trick is to balance the loud-fun Sky Ranch day with a calm-curiosity day at Puzzle Mansion and Yoki House. The ridge food handles the kids better than most Manila destinations because every restaurant has noodles, fried chicken, and french fries on the menu alongside the bulalo.</p>
<h2>Before You Drive</h2>
<p>From Manila, the drive is 90 minutes off-peak via SLEX. Leave Manila by 6 AM Saturday to avoid the worst weekend traffic. Pre-book a Tagaytay hotel with a pool; the kids will demand a swim by midday. Bring car snacks, water bottles, motion-sickness tablets if your kid is prone, and a couple of small toys for the ride.</p>
<h2>Saturday: Arrive, Lunch, Sky Ranch Afternoon</h2>
<p>Drop the bags by midday. Lunch at a ridge restaurant with a kid menu. Most ridge kitchens have fried chicken, spaghetti, and fries for the kids; the parents order bulalo or tawilis. Sit at a table with the Taal view to entertain the kids during the meal.</p>
<p>Sky Ranch in the afternoon. The park has a kid-friendly ride menu: the carousel, the small Ferris wheel, the bumper cars, the kiddie train, the swing rides, and the giant Ferris wheel (the slow one with the Taal view; safe for kids ages four and up). Allow three to four hours. The park gets crowded by 3 PM on weekends so arrive by 2 PM if possible. Snack options are everywhere; the kids will want cotton candy and ice cream.</p>
<p>Back to the hotel by 6 PM for the pool, dinner, and an early sleep. Tagaytay evenings are cool; the kids drop off easily after the long ride day.</p>
<h2>Sunday: Puzzle Mansion, Yoki House, Drive Out</h2>
<p>Late breakfast at the hotel. Mid-morning visit to Puzzle Mansion, the small museum that houses the world's largest collection of completed jigsaw puzzles. Kids love the giant puzzles on the walls; the small puzzle play area at the entrance keeps younger kids busy. Allow 60 to 90 minutes. Small entrance fee, kids get a small discount.</p>
<p>Lunch at a ridge restaurant or at the Puzzle Mansion cafe. The Mahogany Market bulalo strip is fine for kids if they like noodles or rice; the open-air seating means they can move around between bites.</p>
<p>Afternoon at Yoki's Farm in Mendez (20 minutes from the ridge). Yoki's is part theme-house, part farm, with a quirky animal area, a butterfly garden, and a small cave that the kids walk through. The eclectic decor and the farm animals keep kids engaged for two hours. Cheaper than Sky Ranch and less crowded.</p>
<p>Drive out by 3 PM to beat the Sunday return traffic. Build in a break at the SLEX rest stop for the kids to stretch and use the toilet.</p>
<h2>Alternative: Picnic Grove and the Ridge Walk</h2>
<p>If the kids are not in the mood for Sky Ranch or Puzzle Mansion, the alternative is a slow morning at Picnic Grove. The park has wide grass areas where kids can run, cottages for picnic lunches with the Taal view, and a cable car or zip line for older kids who want a thrill. The day-use fee is modest and the kids self-entertain on the grass for hours.</p>
<h2>What to Pack</h2>
<p>The kid Tagaytay list: layers (warm midday, cool evening), comfortable walking shoes, swim clothes for the hotel pool, snacks for the car, water bottles, sunscreen, mosquito repellent for the evenings, kid medications, and a small toy or book for downtime. Tagaytay evenings drop to 19 to 21 degrees on December nights; bring a light jacket for each kid.</p>
<h2>Kid Notes</h2>
<p>Sky Ranch has a kid-friendly height policy; kids below the ride-height minimum can still enjoy the carousel, the small Ferris wheel, and the kiddie train. The big Ferris wheel is safe for kids who can sit calmly for 10 minutes. Puzzle Mansion is quiet; remind kids to use indoor voices. Yoki's Farm allows kids to feed some animals; bring small bills for the feeding stations.</p>
<h2>Getting Around</h2>
<p>A private car is the cleanest option for a Tagaytay kid weekend. The ridge stretches 10 kilometers and tricycle rides are bumpy and not safe for car-seat kids. Most hotels have valet parking or drop-off areas at the entrance.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>December to February is the cool dry window with the cleanest Taal views and the most pleasant evenings. March to May is hotter but still cooler than Manila. Avoid the rainy June to October because the kid-park days get cancelled on heavy rain.</p>
HTML,
        'meta_title' => 'Kid-Friendly Tagaytay: Weekend Actually With Kids | Resort Guru PH',
        'meta_description' => 'A two-day Tagaytay weekend with kids: Sky Ranch afternoon, Puzzle Mansion, Yokis Farm, ridge meals, and pool evenings. Tested with kids 4-12.',
        'tags' => 'Tagaytay, Family Travel, Kid-Friendly, Sky Ranch, Manila Escape',
        'cover_destination_key' => 'tagaytay',
    ],

    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    // 20. KID-FRIENDLY CEBU CITY: THREE-DAY FAMILY PLAN
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.thepoortraveler.net/kid-friendly-cebu/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'The Poor Traveler',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Kid-Friendly Cebu City: A Three-Day Family Plan',
        'slug' => 'kid-friendly-cebu-city-three-day-family-plan',
        'excerpt' => 'A three-day Cebu City family plan with kids: Sirao Garden, Tops Lookout, Cebu Ocean Park, Magellans Cross, and a quiet Mactan beach day.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Cebu City is one of the more underrated kid-friendly Philippine cities because it combines a real urban food scene with mountain viewpoints, a marine park, and a beach side that is only 30 minutes away on Mactan. For families with kids aged five to twelve, three days covers a solid mix without overpacking. The trick is to base in Cebu City for the urban activities and to do one day at Mactan for the beach reset.</p>
<h2>Before You Fly</h2>
<p>Fly Manila to Mactan-Cebu International Airport in one hour 25 minutes. The airport is on Mactan, around 30 minutes by Grab to Cebu City off-peak. Pre-book a city hotel near Ayala Center or IT Park; both areas have kid-friendly restaurants and easy Grab pickups. Bring stroller rentals are easy to find at Cebu malls.</p>
<h2>Day 1: Arrive, Magellan's Cross, Basilica, Carbon Market</h2>
<p>Drop the bags by midday at the city hotel. Lunch at a kid-friendly Cebu kitchen; the Larsian BBQ row is the local favorite but the smoke and crowds can be too much for younger kids. The Original Lechon Belly chain is a safer family option for first-timers.</p>
<p>Afternoon at the heritage triangle: Magellan's Cross, the Basilica del Santo Nino, and Fort San Pedro. The three sites are within a five-minute walk and the walk is paved and shaded in parts. Kids enjoy the basilica for the colorful interiors and the candles. Fort San Pedro has a small fort area with cannons and stone walls that kids climb on; supervise closely.</p>
<p>Back to the hotel by 5 PM for pool and dinner. If the hotel does not have a pool, the IT Park area has open-air dining with kid-friendly menus.</p>
<h2>Day 2: Sirao Garden Morning, Tops Lookout Afternoon</h2>
<p>Early breakfast. By 8 AM, head up the mountain to Sirao Flower Farm, the celosia (cock's comb) flower garden 30 minutes up the JY Square road. The garden has rows of red, yellow, and pink celosia flowers that kids love for photos. The viewpoints over Cebu City below are clear in the morning before the haze. Allow 90 minutes.</p>
<p>Continue to Tops Lookout, the higher viewpoint that gives a 270-degree panorama of Cebu City and the Mactan strait. Tops has paved walkways, a small kids' play area, and food stalls. Small entrance fee. Allow 90 minutes.</p>
<p>Lunch on the mountain at a small carinderia or at Lantaw Native Restaurant in Busay. Lantaw has Filipino kid-menu items and the patio has the city-view backdrop. Back to the hotel by 3 PM for pool and rest.</p>
<p>Dinner at the SM Seaside or Ayala Center mall; both have indoor kid-play areas and easy food courts.</p>
<h2>Day 3: Cebu Ocean Park, Mactan Beach Sunset</h2>
<p>Morning at Cebu Ocean Park near SM Seaside. The park has the underwater tunnel walk, the marine touch pool, the bird show, and the small petting area. Kids love the touch pool the most; supervise so they handle the starfish gently. Allow three to four hours. Pre-book online to skip the gate line.</p>
<p>Lunch at SM Seaside. Drive to Mactan by mid-afternoon (30 minutes Grab). Spend the late afternoon at a Mactan public beach or a day-use resort with a pool and beach access. The Mactan beaches are not as wide as Boracay but they work for a sunset reset with the kids.</p>
<p>Sunset on Mactan, then back to the airport for the evening flight or back to the city hotel for one more night.</p>
<h2>What to Pack</h2>
<p>The Cebu kid list: sunscreen, hats, swim clothes for the pool and the beach, comfortable walking shoes for the heritage triangle, light layers for the air-conditioned malls, mosquito repellent for the mountain visits, water bottles, snacks, kid medications, and a stroller for kids ages two to four.</p>
<h2>Kid Notes</h2>
<p>Cebu has a hot humid climate year-round; the kids will tire faster than they would on a cooler trip. Build in pool time and air-conditioned breaks every half-day. The mall food courts are the easiest kid-meal options; the smaller carinderia kitchens are an experience but the spice level varies. The Cebu kids enjoy puso (hanging rice) and dried mango as souvenirs.</p>
<h2>Getting Around</h2>
<p>Grab works city-wide and is the cleanest family transport. Taxis are fine but the kids' car-seat options are limited; bring your own if you have one. For the mountain visits, hire a van for the half-day; the JY Square jeepneys are not kid-friendly for steep climbs.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>March to June is the dry calm window. November to February is the cool dry window with the cleanest evenings. July to October is the habagat side with afternoon rain; the outdoor activities still work but pack rain gear for the family.</p>
HTML,
        'meta_title' => 'Kid-Friendly Cebu City: Three-Day Family Plan | Resort Guru PH',
        'meta_description' => 'A three-day Cebu City family plan: Sirao Garden, Tops Lookout, Cebu Ocean Park, Magellan Cross, and Mactan sunset. Kid-tested for ages 5-12.',
        'tags' => 'Cebu City, Family Travel, Kid-Friendly, Mactan, Visayas',
        'cover_destination_key' => 'cebu-city',
    ],

    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    // 21. KID-FRIENDLY DAVAO: THREE-DAY FAMILY PLAN
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.alittlewanderlust.com/kid-friendly-davao/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'A Little Wanderlust PH',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Kid-Friendly Davao: A Three-Day Family Plan',
        'slug' => 'kid-friendly-davao-three-day-family-plan',
        'excerpt' => 'A three-day Davao family plan: Crocodile Park, Eden Nature Park, Philippine Eagle Center, and a Samal beach day for the kids.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Davao is the calmer southern Philippine city that families often overlook because it sits a longer flight from Manila. The reward is a city with clean parks, low traffic compared to Cebu or Manila, and a kid-activity menu built around real animal encounters. The three-day plan below uses Davao City as the base for two days and Samal Island for the third day as the beach reset.</p>
<h2>Before You Fly</h2>
<p>Fly Manila to Davao in one hour 50 minutes. The Davao airport is in the city, around 15 minutes by Grab to Lanang or downtown. Pre-book a hotel in Lanang for the easier access to Crocodile Park and Lanang Mall, or in Matina for the nightlife and the food scene. Both have kid-friendly restaurants.</p>
<h2>Day 1: Arrive, Crocodile Park, Lights Show</h2>
<p>Drop the bags by midday. Lunch at a Davao kitchen for the local seafood; the Davao kinilaw uses tabon-tabon and the version is unusual for kids who have only tasted Visayan ceviche. Order grilled tuna belly as the safer first dish.</p>
<p>Afternoon at the Davao Crocodile Park near Lanang. The park has the largest crocodile collection in Mindanao, plus a tiger area, a bird show, and a small petting zoo. Allow three to four hours. The crocodile feeding shows happen on schedule; check the timing on arrival.</p>
<p>Evening at the Lanang Mall area for dinner and the small light shows at Christmas season (if visiting in December). The mall has indoor kid-play areas and the food court is family-friendly.</p>
<h2>Day 2: Eden Nature Park, Philippine Eagle Center</h2>
<p>Early breakfast. By 8 AM, drive 45 minutes south to Eden Nature Park in Toril. Eden is the highland nature park that sits at 800 meters elevation, which makes the air cooler than Davao city itself. The park has a kid-friendly menu: the Skyrider zip cable for older kids, the carriage-style cable ride for younger kids, the flower garden walk, the bamboo grove, and the Indigenous village tour. Allow four to five hours. Lunch at the park's restaurant.</p>
<p>Afternoon at the Philippine Eagle Center in Calinan, 30 minutes from Eden. The center is the breeding sanctuary for the Philippine eagle, the national bird, and the kids see the eagles up close in the open-flight enclosures. The center also has Mindanao deer, monkeys, and reptiles. Allow 90 minutes.</p>
<p>Back to the city by 5 PM. Dinner at a Davao kitchen.</p>
<h2>Day 3: Samal Island Beach Day, Fly Out</h2>
<p>Early breakfast. By 8 AM, drive to Sasa wharf and barge to Samal Island (10 minutes crossing). Spend the day at a Samal beach resort with kid-friendly water: shallow lagoon, calm sea, and a pool for the kids who tire of the sea. Most Samal resorts allow day-use for non-staying guests.</p>
<p>Alternative: a half-day Talicud island banca trip from Samal for the older kids who can handle the boat. Talicud has cleaner water and quieter coves than Samal.</p>
<p>Back to Davao city by mid-afternoon for the evening flight. Allow 90 minutes from the resort to the airport including the barge.</p>
<h2>What to Pack</h2>
<p>The Davao kid list: sunscreen, hats, swim clothes for Samal and the hotel pool, comfortable walking shoes for Eden, mosquito repellent (Davao has more mosquitoes than Cebu or Manila), light layers for the cool Eden air, water bottles, snacks, and kid medications. Bring a small first-aid kit; Davao is generally safe but the park surfaces can scrape.</p>
<h2>Kid Notes</h2>
<p>Davao is known for the durian; older kids might try a small piece as a culinary experience but younger kids will refuse. The pomelo from Davao is the kid-friendly fruit alternative. The Davao chocolate (Malagos brand) is a clean pasalubong that kids love. Crocodile Park staff are family-friendly and the feeding shows are managed safely.</p>
<h2>Getting Around</h2>
<p>Grab works city-wide. Taxis are fine and metered. For the longer trips to Eden and Samal, hire a van for the day; the standalone taxis have meter limits. Bring your own kid car-seat if you have one; the local hired vans typically do not include them.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>March to October is the drier window. November to February is also fine. The wettest months are December and January with afternoon rain. Davao sits south of the typhoon belt so the destination works most months without the storm risks that affect Luzon and the Visayas.</p>
