    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.solotripnotesph.com/digital-nomad-cebu/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Solo Trip Notes PH',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Digital Nomad Cebu City: One Month, IT Park, and the Food Loop',
        'slug' => 'digital-nomad-cebu-city-one-month-coworking-food',
        'excerpt' => 'A one-month Cebu City nomad read: IT Park coworking, Lahug cafes, Larsian BBQ evenings, and weekend trips to Bohol or Moalboal.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Cebu City is the practical nomad base for the Visayas. The IT Park area has the most reliable fibre wifi in the region, the food scene covers everything from lechon to international plates, the airport connects directly to most Asian capitals, and the weekend trips to Bohol, Moalboal, Malapascua, and Bantayan are short. For a one-month focus stay with weekend movement, Cebu earns the time.</p>
<h2>Before You Fly</h2>
<p>Fly Manila or any major Asian city to Mactan-Cebu International Airport. The airport is on Mactan, around 30 minutes by Grab to Cebu City (IT Park or Ayala Center) off-peak. For a one-month stay, secure a serviced apartment in the IT Park, Lahug, or Capitol area. The IT Park has the densest fibre coverage and the most cafes; Lahug and Capitol are quieter alternatives.</p>
<h2>Wifi Reality</h2>
<p>Cebu City fibre is the best in the Visayas. PLDT Home Fibr, Converge, Globe at Home, and Sky Cable all cover the IT Park, Ayala, Lahug, and Capitol areas. Speeds typically run 100 to 500 Mbps download. Brownouts are rare in the IT Park because the area has redundant power. Other parts of the city occasionally see brownouts during summer months.</p>
<h2>Coworking Spots</h2>
<p>IT Park has multiple formal coworking spaces: Worc, Common Ground, and several others. Day passes, weekly memberships, and monthly memberships are available at modest rates. The spaces include desk space, meeting rooms, espresso, fast wifi, and 24-hour access in some cases. For nomads who prefer cafes, the IT Park has dense cafe coverage: Starbucks, Tim Hortons, Coffee Bean, and several local cafes line the strip.</p>
<h2>A One-Month Schedule</h2>
<p>The Cebu nomad rhythm fits the focused-work-weekend-trip pattern. Monday through Friday: morning coffee at the IT Park, focus block at the coworking or a cafe until lunch, lunch at one of the IT Park or Ayala kitchens, second focus block, evening Larsian BBQ or a Filipino dinner, walk back to the apartment. Saturday: weekend trip out of Cebu City. Sunday: long brunch, slow walk, week's grocery run.</p>
<h2>Food</h2>
<p>Cebu City food covers the whole spectrum. For breakfast: the cafes at IT Park for the Western options, the small carinderias for the longganisa Cebu and danggit fish. For lunch: lechon at any of the original Cebu lechon chains, the Larsian BBQ row for the early-lunch grill stations. For dinner: Lantaw Native Restaurant in Lahug for the city-view setting, Casa Verde for the steaks and ribs, the IT Park kitchens for the international cuisine.</p>
<p>For nomads with kitchen access, the Carbon Market is the largest wet market in Cebu and has fresh produce at lowest prices.</p>
<h2>Gym and Movement</h2>
<p>Cebu City has the best gym scene in the Visayas. Anytime Fitness, FitnessFirst, Gold's Gym, and several boutique CrossFit and yoga studios operate around IT Park and Ayala. Monthly memberships at the main chains are reasonable. For runners, the Ayala Park loop and the IT Park outer path work for daily runs.</p>
<h2>Money and Cash</h2>
<p>Cebu City has full banking infrastructure. All major banks have branches and ATMs in the central business districts. Cards work everywhere. GCash and PayMaya are widely accepted. For the smaller carinderias and the Larsian BBQ row, cash is preferred but GCash also works at most stalls now.</p>
<h2>Where to Stay</h2>
<p>For a one-month stay, the IT Park serviced apartments are the cleanest nomad pick. Lahug and Capitol have quieter residential options at lower rates. Skip the downtown Colon area for the noise. Most monthly rentals run 30 to 50 percent below the nightly hotel rate.</p>
<h2>Weekend Trips</h2>
<p>The Cebu nomad weekends are the most varied in the Philippines. Bohol by ferry (2-hour crossing to Tagbilaran). Moalboal by bus (3 hours south). Bantayan or Malapascua by ferry (3-4 hours north). Camotes Islands by ferry (2 hours). Kawasan Falls by bus (3 hours south). The weekend options are deep and varied; the only limit is the calendar.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>The Cebu climate is mild year-round. March to June is the dry calm window for the weekend sea trips. November to February is the cool dry window with the cleanest evenings. July to October has more rain but the city work-life still flows; the ferry trips get rougher.</p>
