    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    // 27. NAIA T1 TO BORACAY: CONNECTING FLIGHT READ
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.wanderingfeetofmine.com/naia-to-boracay/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Wandering Feet of Mine',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'NAIA Terminal 1 to Boracay: A Connecting Flight Read',
        'slug' => 'naia-terminal-1-to-boracay-connecting-flight-read',
        'excerpt' => 'How to connect from NAIA Terminal 1 to Boracay: domestic transfers, the Caticlan or Kalibo choice, and the jetty-port chain for first-timers.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Most international travelers reach Boracay via NAIA Terminal 1, the international arrivals terminal in Manila. The transfer to Boracay requires a domestic connection to Caticlan or Kalibo airport, then a van or bus transfer to the jetty port, then a short boat to the island. Here is the honest first-timer chain.</p>
<h2>Step 1: Clear NAIA Terminal 1</h2>
<p>NAIA Terminal 1 handles most international arrivals into Manila. Allow 60 to 90 minutes from landing to exit, longer during peak hours. The arrival hall has the immigration counters, the baggage claim, the customs check, and the exit doors. Have your Philippine eTravel QR code ready on your phone; the immigration officer will scan it.</p>
<h2>Step 2: Transfer to NAIA Terminal 4 (Domestic Departures)</h2>
<p>Cebu Pacific and AirAsia Manila-to-Caticlan or Manila-to-Kalibo flights depart from NAIA Terminal 4. Philippine Airlines flights depart from NAIA Terminal 2. The inter-terminal transfer requires a shuttle ride; the NAIA shuttle bus is free and runs in a continuous loop between all four terminals. Walk to the shuttle pickup point on the arrival level and wait.</p>
<p>Shuttle wait time can be 15 to 30 minutes. The ride between terminals takes another 10 to 20 minutes depending on the terminal pair. Build in two hours minimum between the international landing and the domestic departure.</p>
<h2>Step 3: Domestic Flight to Caticlan or Kalibo</h2>
<p>Caticlan is the closer airport, 15 minutes by van from the jetty port. Kalibo is the larger airport, 90 minutes by van from the jetty port. Caticlan flights are on smaller turboprop aircraft with weight limits and more weather cancellations. Kalibo flights are on larger jets with more capacity.</p>
<p>For first-timers and travelers with heavy luggage, Kalibo is the more reliable option even with the longer van transfer. For travelers with carry-on only and tight schedules, Caticlan saves the most time. Some travelers fly in via Caticlan and out via Kalibo as a hedge against the Caticlan weather cancellations.</p>
<h2>Step 4: Airport to Jetty Port Van</h2>
<p>At Caticlan airport, several van operators run shuttle services to the jetty port. The ride is 15 minutes. At Kalibo airport, the standard transfer is a 90-minute van ride to the Caticlan jetty port; pre-book through your hotel or via an online booking site.</p>
<p>The van fare includes the environmental fee and the terminal fee in some packages; check the breakdown. The jetty port has a separate boat ticket counter; bring cash or a card for the boat fare.</p>
<h2>Step 5: Jetty Boat to Boracay</h2>
<p>The jetty boat from Caticlan to Cagban port on Boracay is a 15-minute crossing. The fare includes the terminal fee, the environmental fee, and the boat fare. Pay at the ticket counter, then queue for the boarding. Life vests are provided on the boat.</p>
<p>From Cagban port on Boracay, take a tricycle or e-trike to your resort. The fare varies with the resort location; Station 1 is closer than Station 3 from Cagban.</p>
<h2>Total Time Budget</h2>
<p>For first-timers, budget 8 to 10 hours from the NAIA T1 landing to the Boracay hotel. The breakdown is roughly 90 minutes for NAIA T1 exit and shuttle, 60 to 120 minutes for the domestic terminal wait, 60 to 90 minutes for the Manila-Caticlan or Manila-Kalibo flight, 15 to 90 minutes for the airport-jetty van, 30 minutes for the jetty wait and boat crossing, and 15 to 30 minutes for the tricycle ride to the resort.</p>
<p>The single-day chain is doable but tiring. For travelers who land at NAIA T1 in the late afternoon, an overnight in Manila and a morning domestic flight is the cleaner option.</p>
<h2>Booking the Full Chain</h2>
<p>Many Boracay resorts and tour operators sell a single bundled transfer that covers the airport-jetty-boat chain with one ticket and one pickup. The bundled price is slightly higher than the pieces booked separately but saves the haggling at each step. For first-timers, the bundle is worth it.</p>
<h2>Return Transfer</h2>
<p>For the return, allow 4 to 5 hours from the Boracay hotel to the boarding gate at the domestic departure. The reverse chain (tricycle-boat-van-flight) takes time and the jetty queues can be long during peak hours.</p>
