        'excerpt' => 'How to get from Clark International Airport to Subic and the Zambales coast: van, bus, hired car, and the honest drive times to San Antonio and Iba.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Clark International Airport is the alternative to NAIA for travelers heading to the Zambales coast. The drive from Clark to Subic is short, the road network is good, and skipping Manila traffic is the main reason travelers route this way. Here is the transport read for the Clark to Subic and Zambales chain.</p>
<h2>Distance and Drive Times</h2>
<p>From Clark airport to the Subic Bay Freeport gate is around 50 kilometers via SCTEX. Off-peak drive is 50 minutes. Standard weekday drive is 60 to 75 minutes. From Subic to San Antonio (the jump-off for Anawangin and Capones islands) is another 60 kilometers, around 90 minutes. From San Antonio to Iba (the central Zambales coast) is another 60 kilometers, around 90 minutes.</p>
<p>For a single-day transfer from Clark to Iba, budget around 4 to 5 hours including a meal stop.</p>
<h2>Step 1: Clear Clark International Airport</h2>
<p>Clark airport is smaller and faster than NAIA. Allow 30 to 45 minutes from landing to exit for international arrivals, less for domestic. The arrival hall has the immigration, baggage claim, and customs check on a single level. The exit doors open to the parking and transport zone.</p>
<h2>Step 2: Choose Your Transport</h2>
<p>The options from Clark are van, bus, hired car, and self-drive. Grab works in Clark but the supply is thinner than at NAIA.</p>
<h2>Van Transfer</h2>
<p>Several van operators run from Clark to Subic with departures every hour during daytime. The van drops at the Subic boardwalk or the Olongapo terminal depending on the operator. The ride is 60 to 75 minutes off-peak.</p>
<p>For Zambales coast destinations (San Antonio, Iba, Botolan), there is no direct van from Clark. The chain is Clark to Olongapo by van, then Olongapo to the Zambales coast by Victory Liner bus. Total time is 3 to 4 hours.</p>
<h2>Bus</h2>
<p>The Victory Liner bus station in Dau (15 minutes from Clark airport by Grab) has direct buses to Olongapo, Iba, and Sta. Cruz Zambales. The Olongapo bus runs every 30 minutes and the ride is 90 minutes. The Iba and Sta. Cruz buses run less frequently; check the schedule on arrival.</p>
<p>The bus fare is the cheapest of the options. The buses have air conditioning and most have onboard restrooms.</p>
<h2>Hired Private Car</h2>
<p>Pre-book a hired car with a driver from a Clark or Subic rental agency for the cleanest end-to-end transfer. The driver waits at the airport arrival hall with a sign and drives directly to your destination. The rate is two to three times the bus fare but the comfort and the door-to-door service are worth it for families with kids and luggage.</p>
<p>For groups of five or more, a van rental from the same agencies is the better per-head option.</p>
<h2>Self-Drive</h2>
<p>Several car rental agencies operate at Clark airport. For travelers planning a multi-stop Zambales loop (Subic, Anawangin, Iba, Capones), self-drive is the most flexible option. The SCTEX and the Subic-Tipo expressway connect smoothly; the Zambales coastal road from Olongapo to Iba is a single highway that is easy to follow.</p>
<p>Toll fees apply at SCTEX gates. The Zambales coastal road is mostly toll-free.</p>
<h2>Tips for the Transfer</h2>
<p>Bring cash for the SCTEX tolls if self-driving. Pack rain gear for the habagat months; the Zambales coast gets afternoon rain from June to October. Carry a refillable water bottle; the SCTEX rest stops are clean but the food is expensive. The Zambales coast is hot and humid year-round; have light cotton clothing in the carry-on.</p>
<h2>Common Mistakes</h2>
<p>Do not assume that the Grab supply at Clark is the same as NAIA. The wait time can be 30 to 60 minutes during peak hours. Pre-book a van or hire a car if you are not flexible. Do not plan a late-arrival transfer to Iba in the same day; the Zambales coastal road has no street lighting and the drive is risky after dark.</p>
<h2>When to Arrive at Clark</h2>
<p>The best Clark arrival window for a Zambales onward transfer is between 6 AM and 11 AM. The roads are clear and the chain completes by mid-afternoon. The worst window is 4 PM to 8 PM; the chain extends past sunset and the Zambales coast becomes a nighttime drive.</p>
<h2>Return Transfer</h2>
<p>For the return, allow 3 to 4 hours from the Zambales coast to the Clark airport gate. The reverse chain (bus to Olongapo, van to Clark) takes time and the buses leave on fixed schedules. For an evening flight from Clark, leave Iba by noon.</p>
