    // 38. GLUTEN-FREE PHILIPPINES CELIAC BY DESTINATION
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.alittlewanderlust.com/gluten-free-philippines/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'A Little Wanderlust PH',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Gluten-Free Philippines: A Celiac Read by Destination',
        'slug' => 'gluten-free-philippines-celiac-by-destination',
        'excerpt' => 'A celiac-friendly Philippines read: rice-based Filipino dishes, the soy-sauce caveat, gluten-free cafes by city, and cross-contamination tips.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>The Philippines is one of the easier Asian countries for celiac and gluten-free travelers because rice is the default carbohydrate at almost every meal. Most traditional Filipino dishes are naturally gluten-free in their core form. The main risks are soy sauce (which contains wheat in most Filipino brands), the breaded dishes, and the cross-contamination at kitchens that handle wheat noodles. Here is the destination-by-destination read.</p>
<h2>The Big Risks</h2>
<p>Most Philippine soy sauce brands (Silver Swan, Datu Puti) contain wheat. The naturally gluten-free alternative is patis (fish sauce) or coconut aminos. For dishes that use soy sauce (adobo, marinated meats, fried rice), confirm the soy-sauce brand or ask for a no-soy-sauce version.</p>
<p>Breaded dishes (chicken katsu, breaded fish, lumpia wrappers) contain wheat. The lumpia wrapper is wheat-based; the lumpiang ubod is wheat-wrapped. Pancit noodles are wheat-based; ask for rice noodles or skip.</p>
<p>Cross-contamination is real at the small carinderia kitchens where the same pan and oil handle both wheat and rice dishes. For severe celiac, the smaller kitchens are higher risk than the larger restaurants with separate prep areas.</p>
<h2>Naturally Gluten-Free Filipino Dishes</h2>
<p>Sinigang in its pure form (vegetables and meat in tamarind broth) is gluten-free; verify the bouillon used. Tinola (chicken in ginger soup) is gluten-free in the traditional version. Nilaga (boiled beef with vegetables) is gluten-free. Kinilaw (Visayan ceviche with vinegar and calamansi) is gluten-free if no soy sauce is added.</p>
<p>Grilled dishes (inihaw na isda, inihaw na liempo) are gluten-free if not marinated in wheat-based soy sauce; ask. Lechon is naturally gluten-free; the dipping sauces vary so confirm. Crispy pata is gluten-free if not breaded.</p>
<p>Rice dishes (plain rice, garlic rice without soy sauce, sinangag adjusted) are gluten-free. Most breakfast silog plates can be adapted to be gluten-free by skipping the wheat-based components.</p>
<h2>Manila</h2>
<p>Manila has the most gluten-free options. Wildflour Cafe, Edgy Veggie, and Pipino in Quezon City have explicit gluten-free menus. Salad Stop and Single Origin have gluten-free options. The international restaurants in Makati and BGC are more reliable for strict celiac than the local kitchens.</p>
<h2>Cebu City and Davao</h2>
<p>Cebu City has fewer gluten-free options but several cafes in IT Park have gluten-free baked goods and breads. Davao has a few gluten-free cafes and the Mindanao food scene leans towards rice-based dishes that work for celiac travelers.</p>
<h2>Tagaytay</h2>
<p>Tagaytay has gluten-free baked goods at Bag of Beans and a few ridge cafes. The bulalo and most Filipino dishes at Mahogany Market are naturally gluten-free; ask about the soy sauce. Sonya's Garden has gluten-aware staff.</p>
<h2>Boracay</h2>
<p>Boracay has several international restaurants with gluten-free options. Real Coffee has gluten-free baked goods. Pizzeria-style kitchens often offer gluten-free pizza bases on request. The seafood grills along the beach are mostly gluten-free in their grilled-fish form.</p>
<h2>El Nido and Palawan</h2>
<p>El Nido has a few gluten-aware cafes catering to the international crowd. Most Filipino kitchens can prepare a gluten-free grilled fish with rice and vegetables. The tour-boat lunches are not gluten-free certified; bring backup snacks.</p>
<h2>Cross-Contamination Risks</h2>
<p>For travelers with severe celiac (not just sensitivity), the cross-contamination risk is real. The same wok used for pancit (wheat noodles) is often used for rice dishes. The same fryer for breaded chicken is often used for plain chicken. For strict celiac, eat at restaurants with separate prep areas (typically the international chains and the higher-end Filipino restaurants).</p>
<h2>Tips for Travelers</h2>
<p>Learn the key Tagalog phrases: walang trigo (no wheat), walang toyo (no soy sauce), walang harina (no flour), gluten-free po. The phrases are starting to be understood in the bigger tourist cities but the rural carinderias may not know the term.</p>
<p>Carry gluten-free snacks for the longer travel days. Long bus rides and remote areas have fewer options. The packed cooler with gluten-free crackers, hummus, fruit, and rice cakes is a clean travel set.</p>
<h2>Common Mistakes</h2>
<p>Do not assume Filipino fried rice is gluten-free; most uses wheat-based soy sauce. Do not assume vinegar dipping sauces are gluten-free; some include soy sauce. Do not skip checking the kalamansi-based marinades for added soy. Do not eat from the lumpia and pancit displays at any kitchen; the cross-contamination risk is high.</p>
<p>For severe celiac, the safest strategy is to stick with grilled fish, grilled meats, plain rice, and steamed vegetables, with all sauces ordered on the side or skipped. The simple option avoids most of the gluten landmines.</p>
HTML,
        'meta_title' => 'Gluten-Free Philippines: Celiac Read by Destination | Resort Guru PH',
        'meta_description' => 'A celiac and gluten-free Philippines guide: safe Filipino dishes, the soy-sauce caveat, gluten-free cafes by city, and cross-contamination tips.',
        'tags' => 'Gluten-Free, Celiac, Philippines Travel, Travel Ops, Dietary',
        'cover_destination_key' => 'manila',
    ],

    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    // 39. COUPLES THREE-DAY EL NIDO: DAY-BY-DAY PLAN
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://taraletsanywhere.com/couples-three-day-el-nido/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Tara Lets Anywhere',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Couples Three-Day El Nido: A Day-by-Day Itinerary',
        'slug' => 'couples-three-day-el-nido-day-by-day-plan',
        'excerpt' => 'A three-day El Nido couple itinerary that hits one shared tour, one private lagoon morning, and a Las Cabanas sunset finish.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>El Nido in three days for a couple is the short-trip version of the longer five-day or week-long honeymoon plans. The trick is to pick one boat day, one beach day, and one slow town day, and to skip the longer drives to Nacpan or the inland falls. Here is the tight day-by-day for couples on a long weekend.</p>
<h2>Before You Fly</h2>
<p>Fly Manila to Lio Airport via AirSWIFT; the 10-minute transfer to town is the cleanest start. The Puerto Princesa to El Nido van transfer (five hours) eats too much of the short trip. Pre-book the accommodation, the boat tour for Day 2, and the airport transfer.</p>
<h2>Day 1: Arrive, Slow Town Afternoon, Las Cabanas Sunset</h2>
<p>Land at Lio by midday or early afternoon. Drop the bags at the accommodation. Late lunch at a town kitchen, then a slow walk through the El Nido town beach. The first afternoon is the rest-and-acclimate window; do not book anything strenuous.</p>
<p>By 4 PM, take a tricycle to Las Cabanas Beach (15 minutes from town). Las Cabanas is the sunset beach of El Nido. Order a couple of drinks from a beachfront bar, watch the sun set across the Bacuit Bay islands, and let the trip start at the right pace. Dinner at Las Cabanas or back in town.</p>
<h2>Day 2: Private Tour (Big Lagoon, Small Lagoon, Helicopter Beach)</h2>
<p>Wake up at 7 AM. Coffee at the accommodation, then board the private banca by 8 AM. The standard couple route is the Tour A run with a private boat: Big Lagoon at opening hour (before the shared-tour crowds arrive at 10 AM), Small Lagoon by kayak from the banca, then Shimizu or Helicopter Beach for a beach lunch. The private boat gives you control over the timing and the lunch stop.</p>
<p>Reef shoes are mandatory for the Big Lagoon entry; the rocky edge cuts bare feet. Reef-safe sunscreen, a hat, a long-sleeve rash guard, and a dry bag for the phone are the standard couple boat-day kit.</p>
<p>Back to town by 4 PM. Sunset on the town beach or a quiet hotel-pool soak. Dinner at one of the back-street kitchens that the boat-day crowd does not find. The El Nido side streets serve better grilled fish than the main strip.</p>
<h2>Day 3: Slow Morning, Pack, Fly Out</h2>
<p>Sleep in. Late breakfast on the balcony or at a town cafe. By mid-morning, walk to Caalan Beach, a 15-minute slow walk north of town. Caalan is the quietest stretch near the town; the morning light is the cleanest of the day.</p>
<p>Lunch at a town kitchen, then pack. Tricycle to Lio Airport for the afternoon flight back to Manila. Most flights depart Lio by mid-afternoon; build in 90 minutes from the room to the boarding gate.</p>
<h2>Couple Notes</h2>
<p>Three days is tight. The honest read is that El Nido deserves five days minimum to do without rushing. For couples who only have three, the priority order is: one boat day (Tour A private), one Las Cabanas sunset, one slow town morning. Skip Nacpan (the 90-minute drive each way eats too much time), skip the inland falls, skip Tour C (the longer Hidden Beach route).</p>
<h2>What to Pack</h2>
<p>The three-day couple list: a swim outfit each, reef shoes for the lagoon entry, a long-sleeve rash guard, a wide-brim hat, reef-safe sunscreen, a small dry bag, a refillable water bottle, light evening clothing for the town dinners, and a small first-aid kit. The El Nido humidity is high so pack quick-dry clothes.</p>
<h2>Where to Stay</h2>
<p>For a three-day trip, stay in El Nido town proper to maximize the walking access to dinners and the morning beach walks. The Corong-Corong area is the quieter alternative but adds a tricycle ride to the town center. Avoid staying at Lio if you only have three days; the resort isolation cuts you off from the town food scene.</p>
<h2>Getting Around</h2>
<p>Tricycles handle the town and the runs to Las Cabanas and Caalan. The boat operator picks up at the town beach for Day 2. No scooter rental needed for three days. Cash is preferred everywhere; the ATMs are limited so withdraw on arrival.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>December to early May is the dry window with the cleanest sea conditions. February and early March are the quietest months. Avoid Holy Week and Christmas because the boat tours fill up and the prices spike.</p>
<h2>Day-3 Alternatives</h2>
<p>If you have an extra half-day before the flight, consider a half-day Tour D (Cadlao Lagoon and Pasandigan Cove) instead of the slow morning. Tour D ends by 1 PM and still leaves time for an afternoon flight. The half-day option packs more into the trip without becoming exhausting.</p>
HTML,
        'meta_title' => 'Couples Three-Day El Nido: Day-by-Day Itinerary | Resort Guru PH',
        'meta_description' => 'A three-day El Nido couple plan: arrive and Las Cabanas sunset, private Tour A, slow town morning. Tight long-weekend itinerary with Tour D backup.',
        'tags' => 'El Nido, Couple Travel, Three-Day Plan, Itinerary, Palawan',
