    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    // 40. COUPLES FIVE-DAY BORACAY: DAY-BY-DAY PLAN
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.wanderingfeetofmine.com/couples-five-day-boracay/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Wandering Feet of Mine',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Couples Five-Day Boracay: A Day-by-Day Itinerary',
        'slug' => 'couples-five-day-boracay-day-by-day-plan',
        'excerpt' => 'A five-day Boracay couple plan: Station 1 slow days, island-hopping mid-trip, helmet diving, Mount Luho viewpoint, and Bulabog sunrise.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Boracay in five days for a couple is the comfortable mid-length trip that fits between a long weekend and a full honeymoon week. The plan splits between two slow beach days, two activity days, and one slow last morning. The trick for couples is to base on Station 1 for the quieter beach side and walk down to the busier Station 2 only for the dinner scene.</p>
<h2>Before You Fly</h2>
<p>Fly Manila to Caticlan (closer to the jetty) or to Kalibo (larger airport, longer transfer). For a five-day trip with checked bags, Kalibo is the more reliable option. The transfer chain (airport-van-jetty-boat-tricycle to resort) takes 90 minutes from Caticlan and 2.5 hours from Kalibo. Pre-book the bundled transfer through the resort.</p>
<h2>Day 1: Arrive, Slow Walk, Station 1 Sunset</h2>
<p>Drop the bags by midday at a Station 1 resort. Lunch at a beachfront kitchen. Walk the beach from Willy's Rock south to D'Mall (25 minutes) to orient yourselves to the strip. End back at Station 1 for the late afternoon. Sunset on the beach at 5:45 PM. Dinner at a Station 1 kitchen or at the D'Mall food strip.</p>
<h2>Day 2: Island-Hopping (Private Banca)</h2>
<p>Wake up at 7 AM. Board the private banca by 8:30 AM. The standard couple route hits Crystal Cove for the morning swim, Puka Beach for the long shell-sand walk and lunch, then back to White Beach by mid-afternoon. The private boat (rather than shared) gives you control over the lunch stop and skips the snorkel pairs you do not need.</p>
<p>Back to the resort by 3 PM. Nap, then a slow beach evening. Sunset, dinner, early sleep.</p>
<h2>Day 3: Helmet Diving or Parasailing, Slow Afternoon</h2>
<p>Late breakfast on the beach. Mid-morning, walk to the watersports operators near the Station 1 to Station 2 boundary. Pick one activity: helmet diving for the gentle underwater experience, or parasailing for the aerial view. Both are 30-minute activities. Couples who do both should book the morning helmet dive and the afternoon parasail.</p>
<p>Lunch at the beach. Afternoon slow on the loungers or a couples massage at the resort spa. Sunset, dinner.</p>
<h2>Day 4: Mount Luho, Bulabog Side, Slow Afternoon</h2>
<p>Morning e-trike ride to Mount Luho, the highest viewpoint on Boracay. The 360-degree view of White Beach, Bulabog, and the smaller north coves is the postcard. Allow 90 minutes including travel and the photo time.</p>
<p>Continue to the Bulabog Beach side (the east coast). Bulabog is the kiteboarding side during habagat months and the calmer family beach during amihan months. The walk across the island from Station 1 is 15 minutes; the e-trike covers it in five.</p>
<p>Back to the Station 1 side by lunch. Afternoon slow on the beach. Sunset, dinner.</p>
<h2>Day 5: Bulabog Sunrise, Pack, Fly Out</h2>
<p>Wake up at 5 AM for the Bulabog sunrise. The east coast sunrise is the rarely-taken Boracay photo; most visitors only see the White Beach sunset. Walk back across the island to Station 1 for breakfast.</p>
<p>Slow morning at the resort. Late checkout if available. Transfer chain back to Caticlan or Kalibo by mid-afternoon. Build in three to four hours from the resort to the boarding gate.</p>
<h2>Couple Notes</h2>
<p>Five days lets you do all the standard Boracay activities without rushing. The Station 1 base means quiet evenings and walking access to the busier Station 2 if you want a night out. The private island-hopping boat is the splurge that makes the most difference; the shared boats pack 30 strangers.</p>
<h2>What to Pack</h2>
<p>The Boracay couple list: swim outfits, reef shoes for the snorkel stops, a long-sleeve rash guard, a wide-brim hat, reef-safe sunscreen, a small dry bag, beachfront-cover-ups for the walks, light evening clothing for dinners, and a small first-aid kit. The Boracay humidity is high; pack quick-dry clothes.</p>
<h2>Where to Stay</h2>
<p>Station 1 has the quietest stretch of beach with the widest sand and the talong palms shade. Station 2 has the food and bar scene but the beachfront is louder. Station 3 has the cheaper accommodation but the longest walk to the central strip. For a couple, Station 1 is the cleanest pick. The beachfront properties on Station 1 are the splurge that the photos are for.</p>
<h2>Getting Around</h2>
<p>Tricycles and e-trikes handle the island. The new e-trikes are quieter and easier to board. Cash works almost everywhere; cards are accepted at the bigger restaurants and resorts. Grab does not operate on Boracay.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>November to May is the dry amihan season with the calm sea conditions. February and September are the quietest months in the dry window. December and Holy Week are the most crowded. June to October is the habagat side; the wind shifts and the swimming moves to Bulabog.</p>
<h2>Alternative: Day-Trip to Ariel's Point</h2>
<p>For couples who want one extra activity, Ariel's Point is a full-day cliff-jumping and snorkel boat trip to a private cliff on the mainland. The trip leaves Boracay by mid-morning and returns at sunset. The cliffs offer five to fifteen-meter jumps, and the lunch on the property is good. Add this on Day 3 instead of helmet diving if cliff jumping appeals.</p>
